WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:24.600
&gt;&gt; Mark Sweeney: Good
afternoon and welcome

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:26.610
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:26.610 --> 00:00:29.900
I'm Mark Sweeney, the acting
Deputy Librarian of Congress.

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:31.410
And it's my pleasure
to welcome you

00:00:31.410 --> 00:00:35.250
to the library's historic Thomas
Jefferson Building for which

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:37.920
to this afternoon's symposium,
the first public event

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:42.370
in the United States related to
the Georgian Papers Programme.

00:00:42.370 --> 00:00:44.630
Launched in April of 2015,

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:47.760
the Georgian Papers Programme
is a collaborative effort led

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:52.070
by King's College London and
the Royal Collection Trust

00:00:52.070 --> 00:00:55.300
to make an accessible and
extraordinary rich collection

00:00:55.300 --> 00:00:58.700
of primary source material
from the Georgian monarchs,

00:00:58.700 --> 00:01:02.190
including King George III,
the British monarch in power

00:01:02.190 --> 00:01:05.530
when the American colonies
declared independence.

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:11.170
Comprising nearly 350,000
pages of correspondents, maps,

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:14.640
and royal household
ledgers, the Georgian Papers,

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:20.080
85% of which have been
unknown to scholars until now,

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:23.000
stand to revolutionize
our understanding

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.850
of 18th century British,
American, and Atlantic history,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.240
an era of profound
cultural, political, economic,

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:37.640
and social change in many ways
continues to influence us today.

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:41.930
Last year, in one of the first
acts as Librarian of Congress,

00:01:41.930 --> 00:01:43.980
Dr. Carla Hayden
signed an agreement

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:48.220
with King's College London
and the Royal Collection Trust

00:01:48.220 --> 00:01:51.550
to collaborate on
digitization, dissemination,

00:01:51.550 --> 00:01:55.080
and interpretation of the
papers of King George III

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:58.430
and the other Georgian
Papers' materials.

00:01:58.430 --> 00:02:00.250
Over the next four years,

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:03.010
the Georgian Papers
Programme promises

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:04.850
to reveal many more dimensions

00:02:04.850 --> 00:02:08.560
to Britain's longest reigning
king, allowing scholars

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:11.880
and the general public a
unique window into the life

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:13.410
and times of King George III.

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:17.300
The Library of Congress
holds the papers

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:21.240
of numerous United States
founders, including those

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:25.210
of George Washington, offering
historical context when paired

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:28.280
with the documents of
the Georgian Papers.

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:30.430
As such, it is quite
fitting for us

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:33.500
to actively embrace this
project, and my colleagues

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:36.220
and I are delighted to partner
with our peers both here

00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:39.730
in the United States
and across the pond.

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:43.010
The Omohundro Institute
of Early American History

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:46.010
and Culture is the
primary US partner

00:02:46.010 --> 00:02:48.340
for the Georgian
Papers Programme.

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:50.780
The Library of Congress
joins the Sons

00:02:50.780 --> 00:02:52.670
of the American Revolution

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:56.630
and the Mount Vernon Ladies'
Association as a critical part

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:59.610
of the American Collaboration.

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:02.360
This afternoon's
symposium is hosted

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:06.600
by the John W. Kluge Center
at the Library of Congress

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:09.030
in partnership with
the Omohundro Institute

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:11.450
and King's College London.

00:03:11.450 --> 00:03:14.400
The Kluge Center brings together
scholars and researchers

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:16.440
from around the world
to stimulate

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.190
and energize one
another to distill wisdom

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:22.400
from the library's rich
resources and to interact

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:25.720
with policymakers and
the general public.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.520
In a few moments, we will
hear from four scholars

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:30.790
who were recently
among the first

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:35.080
to examine the Georgian
Papers held at Windsor Castle.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:39.240
Each scholar's presentation will
reveal their early findings,

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:40.550
describing for us some

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:45.290
of the remarkable historical
discoveries that are being made.

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:47.240
But before introducing them,

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:49.080
a few important announcements
related

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:53.320
to the library's participation
in Georgian Papers Programme.

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:59.770
First, a major exhibition, the
Two Georges is planned for 2020,

00:03:59.770 --> 00:04:04.770
2021 to explore the overlapping
worlds of King George III

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:08.690
and George Washington, two
globally significant figures

00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:10.890
of the late 18th century.

00:04:10.890 --> 00:04:14.050
The exhibition, exploring the
commonalities and contrast

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:16.880
between the two men and
the global, political,

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:20.790
and cultural context of their
lives will open first here

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:22.480
at the Library of Congress

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:25.340
and subsequently at
a venue in London.

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:28.430
More details to come on
this exciting project

00:04:28.430 --> 00:04:30.290
as it continues to develop.

00:04:30.290 --> 00:04:33.510
And second, for those of
you who may be inspired

00:04:33.510 --> 00:04:35.910
by today's event,
the library is proud

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:40.140
to announce a new
Georgian Papers fellowship.

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:43.360
Interested scholars may apply
for a two-month fellowship

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:46.780
to pursue independent
research in the Georgian Papers

00:04:46.780 --> 00:04:49.110
of the Royal Archives at Windsor

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:51.570
and in the Early American
Collection at the Library

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:55.490
of Congress with one month
in residence in London

00:04:55.490 --> 00:04:58.960
and one month in residence
here at the library.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:02.470
The application deadline for the
Georgian Papers fellowship is

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:06.910
January 31, 2018, and the
fellowship recipient will be

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:09.810
selected based on the
relevance of their project

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:12.400
for research at both
institutions.

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:16.190
For more details, please
visit the Kluge Center website

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:21.570
at loc.gov/kluge.

