00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:55.740
So thank you, everybody,
who's made that possible.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:09:00.640
So, my task this afternoon is
to introduce the Georgian Papers

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:03.590
and to say a little bit about
the project as a preface

00:09:03.590 --> 00:09:06.000
to the reflections you will
hear from my colleagues

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.240
about their actual
researches into the program.

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:11.840
So they will be giving you the
hardcore research findings.

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:14.980
I'm going to try and give you a
sense about just how interesting

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:17.740
and exciting a program this is.

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:22.460
Now, I have to confess because
I'm a bit of an archives junkie.

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:24.640
I've spent the last 30 years on

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:27.440
and off investigating
the contents of archives

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:30.890
across the UK, some of which
are state-of-the-art archives

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:35.310
with the computer catalogs and
advanced access arrangements,

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:36.610
and others which conform

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:39.250
about the more popular
stereotype archives

00:09:39.250 --> 00:09:42.720
with stone clad vaults
and cobweb documents.

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:44.640
The contents of which is
rather hard to predict

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:47.670
since we've actually blown the
dust physically off the boxes

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.330
and ledgers.

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:51.130
On the other hand, in
my capacity as director

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:53.380
of the clergy database
you just heard about,

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:55.910
I've also had 20 years
experience working getting

00:09:55.910 --> 00:09:58.440
archival documents
online in the form

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:00.880
where the wider public can
access them and scholars

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.220
across the world
make use of them.

00:10:03.220 --> 00:10:05.700
So if you think of the
two unique selling points

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:08.720
of Georgian Papers as
archival and online,

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:10.120
you might think this just feel

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:12.580
like another day at
the office for me.

00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:14.380
That's far from it.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:16.920
The Georgian Papers
are different

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:19.350
and I find myself absolutely
caught up in the excitement

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:21.740
that all my colleagues
here feel for the project.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:24.110
I just hope I can get some of
that excitement across this.

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:25.540
I've been told to be lively.

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:28.690
I'll do my best with my cold,
but we'll see how we get on.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:30.730
So a good place to start.

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:32.910
Well, maybe the actual archive

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:35.390
in which the Georgian
Papers are held.

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:38.760
Now in all kinds of ways,
this Windsor Castle conforms

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:41.050
to the archive as
impenetrable treasure chest

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:43.690
of popular imagination
and something

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:45.640
of that I think is
captured in the documentary

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:49.700
that BBC made a year ago to
introduce the Georgian Papers,

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:51.510
"The Genius of the Mad King".

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:56.970
[ Music ]

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.000
&gt;&gt; [Background Music] Windsor
Castle is the treasure chest

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.700
of royal secrets.

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:04.140
Here in the round tower
are the personal papers

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:08.830
of all British monarchs
and their families

00:11:08.830 --> 00:11:15.490
from George III right down
to Elizabeth the second.

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:18.920
They've always been
out of bounds,

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:24.970
except to a few select
historians.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:31.430
&gt;&gt; Documents that really
you're wanting to keep forever,

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:40.590
you think about a
strong place to put them.

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:46.380
And in the case of Windsor
Castle, the very strongest place

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:48.620
to put them is inside
the round tower.

00:11:48.620 --> 00:11:52.600
And the round tower
is built on the site

00:11:52.600 --> 00:11:59.700
where William the Conqueror
founded the castle in 1070.

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:09.180
And that settles the round tower
oval to the mid 12th century,

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:11.410
so for very sensible and very
secure place to keep papers.

00:12:11.410 --> 00:12:12.710
&gt;&gt; Nowhere safer?

00:12:12.710 --> 00:12:14.010
&gt;&gt; Nowhere safer?

00:12:14.010 --> 00:12:15.310
&gt;&gt; What's happening
here at the top

00:12:15.310 --> 00:12:16.610
of these 104 stone steps
is history of sorts too.

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:17.910
Nearly two centuries
after George III's death,

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:19.210
all his private papers,
hundreds of thousands

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:20.510
of them are being
released to the world.

00:12:20.510 --> 00:12:21.810
Now some may ask, why
has it taken so long?

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:23.110
But here in this fortified royal
vault, it's groundbreaking.

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:24.410
&gt;&gt; Never before has a group

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:25.710
of academics been allowed inside
the inner sanctum to rifle

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:27.010
through these invaluable
documents.

00:12:27.010 --> 00:12:28.310
So the first visit of scholars
from King's College London,

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:29.610
partners in this project, was
a kind of royal revolution.

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:30.910
&gt;&gt; If you could break
yourself into groups

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:32.710
of three or four [inaudible].

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:43.270
[ Inaudible ]

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:44.570
&gt;&gt; Arthur Burns: So that's--

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:46.140
So from now I'm reporting
on that fondling

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:48.130
that was just described there.

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:52.170
And I think that does capture
just how difficult an archive

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:55.050
this has been to access in the
past, which is why we estimate,

00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:57.650
as you already heard, that
despite the obvious importance,

00:12:57.650 --> 00:12:59.850
only some 15% of the papers

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:02.700
which it contains have
ever been published.

00:13:02.700 --> 00:13:07.110
In terms merely of its size,
with some 350,000 pages

00:13:07.110 --> 00:13:09.340
of documents to appear
by the time the program

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:11.890
on digitization concludes,
this is clearly one

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:13.550
of the most significant
caches of 18th

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:15.670
and early 19th century papers

00:13:15.670 --> 00:13:16.970
that will be made
widely available

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:18.270
to new audience for decades.

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:22.900
And it's not only a matter of
making available digital images

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:24.320
of the documents online.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:25.730
The documents fit formally.

00:13:25.730 --> 00:13:27.140
You could only get
to it by going to sit

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:29.540
in this glamorous reading room.

00:13:29.540 --> 00:13:31.290
It sometimes feels a bit
like the historical versions

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:33.420
of prince and sleeping
beauties of hacking your way

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:36.030
into the round tower together.

00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:39.700
Or indeed, so we're going
to digitize them, yes.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:41.820
But of course, it's not just
the question of digitization

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:43.690
because some of the documents
are damaged and they have

00:13:43.690 --> 00:13:48.880
to be conserved first before
they could be made available.

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:51.890
We also don't have a proper
catalog of these documents.

00:13:51.890 --> 00:13:55.060
So a key aspect of the project
is going to be making a catalog

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:57.600
so we actually can describe
these documents the way it

00:13:57.600 --> 00:13:59.380
should be confined with
appropriate metadata.

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:02.410
And we're probably going to
transcribe a fair number of them

00:14:02.410 --> 00:14:04.780
as well into machine
readable text,

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:07.180
which for the first time enables
scholars really to engage

00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:10.400
with these documents
in a serious way.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.760
So, so far I think that document
should capture something

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:17.380
important but it also obscures
one or two key features

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:19.820
of the archives to make
it all the more intriguing

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:21.620
to us scholars.

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:24.410
And obviously one thing
that is obvious for this,

00:14:24.410 --> 00:14:26.150
we thought all about George III.

00:14:26.150 --> 00:14:29.680
We said George-- that there's
a lot about George III in here

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:31.620
and George III is obviously
of particular interest

00:14:31.620 --> 00:14:32.920
with transatlantic audience

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:34.370
because of his rather
painful role

00:14:34.370 --> 00:14:36.110
in the creation of your nation.

00:14:36.110 --> 00:14:39.150
And the sense also that
he has a very long reign.

00:14:39.150 --> 00:14:40.720
I mean he does stay around--

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:43.350
the longest reigning
monarch we have.

00:14:43.350 --> 00:14:44.650
But it's really important,

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:47.640
don't forget this archive
also contains papers relating

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:50.410
to other monarchs, in
fact four of the monarchs.

00:14:50.410 --> 00:14:53.820
George I came to
the throne in 1714.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:55.120
His successor George II,

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:58.920
who reigned until George
III succeeded him in 1760.

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:01.840
And a much more significant
number of documents relating

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:05.830
to George's success of his
son George IV both as king

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:07.940
and when he was Prince
of Wales and regent.

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:11.520
And finally, there's a smaller
bunch of documents that relate

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:14.700
to the reign of William IV
under his death in 1837,

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:16.730
Victoria took the throne.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:19.110
So the archive that gets
this inside is right

00:15:19.110 --> 00:15:21.090
across the Hanoverian
period which even

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:23.620
without the American Revolution
would surely count as one

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:26.670
of the most significant
periods of British history.

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:29.450
Moreover, the archive also
contains papers relating

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:31.450
to many other members
of the royal family,

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:33.030
such as the monarchs' consorts

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:36.550
and children who's often
owned rather turbulent lives--

00:15:36.550 --> 00:15:39.240
and there were some really
quite extraordinary life stories

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:41.220
in the immediate
family of the king.

00:15:41.220 --> 00:15:45.270
Of equal interest to those
are the monarchs themselves.

00:15:45.270 --> 00:15:48.080
Secondly, I think the
emphasis in the documentary,

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:50.990
the vault-like security
of Windsor Castle needs

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:54.250
to be balanced by the fact that
these archives weren't there

00:15:54.250 --> 00:15:58.000
for a long time and they didn't
arrive there in the present form

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.430
until the early 20th century.

00:16:00.430 --> 00:16:03.010
The bulk of the collection
has been left by George IV

00:16:03.010 --> 00:16:05.570
to the care of his executor,
who just happened to be the Duke

00:16:05.570 --> 00:16:07.940
of Wellington with
the instruction

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:09.360
to be destroyed unread.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:13.970
Well, luckily for us, the
instruction was largely ignored

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:16.460
and as was the collection
itself until it was rediscovered

00:16:16.460 --> 00:16:18.580
in 1912 in the basements

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:20.780
of Wellington's Apsley
House then transferred

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:23.830
to its present home in 1914.

00:16:23.830 --> 00:16:26.640
So some records have
ever been consigned

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:29.040
to the fire before it went
to Wellington are bits

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:31.850
of the royal records which
clearly were not [inaudible]

00:16:31.850 --> 00:16:33.780
of Queen Charlotte's
papers and disappeared.

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:36.090
Some of George III's early
papers have disappeared.

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:37.390
And that's the most
distressing one.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:39.370
The years when George is dealing
with the other [inaudible]

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:41.300
in which a lot of
key policies relating

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:42.900
to North America
were being discussed,

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:45.330
some of those papers we
think are just missing.

00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:48.090
Others suffer from the
neglect in the interim.

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:50.670
We do have damaged
documents from damp and all

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:52.600
of those other things reflect
things have not properly been

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:55.870
kept from the years
in Apsley House.

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:58.580
And this means we don't
therefore have a complete set

00:16:58.580 --> 00:17:00.680
of all these monarchs' papers.

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:03.270
But against that,
we can set the fact

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.400
that these collections had been
augmented by gifts and purchases

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:09.650
which extended coverage to many
key men and women of the court

00:17:09.650 --> 00:17:11.680
or the employee of the monarchs.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:13.470
And we were already finding
that some of the key discoveries

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:14.770
that some of you will hear

00:17:14.770 --> 00:17:17.020
about later are being made
among these tapes of the papers

00:17:17.020 --> 00:17:19.070
that were those closely
associated

00:17:19.070 --> 00:17:20.850
with the king [inaudible]
the king himself.

00:17:20.850 --> 00:17:23.520
And those have not been
investigated anyway near as much

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:26.730
as the papers of George III's
own handwriting on them.

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.820
And then there were odd
additional items and of

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:31.690
such things of now that
are usually lurking

00:17:31.690 --> 00:17:35.260
under that catchall title,
miscellaneous in the catalog.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:37.280
And one such curiosity which
I think illustrates the kind

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.610
of things you can find
there is a pair of letters

00:17:39.610 --> 00:17:42.960
from Admiral Lord Horatio
Nelson to Emma Hamilton.

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:45.570
And you can see a
little bit of one here.

00:17:45.570 --> 00:17:47.940
Now, it's not hard to
assess why these documents

00:17:47.940 --> 00:17:50.190
which have no immediate
or thorough connection

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:52.920
with the royal family end
up in the royal archives

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:56.600
in the 20th century for
in them Nelson warns Emma

00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:58.590
that he's heard that the
Prince of Wales wants her

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:02.010
for her mistress and he's
trying to persuade her to stay

00:18:02.010 --> 00:18:04.030
out of any contact with him

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:06.700
in any place lest this
happens [inaudible]

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:10.410
of events today this document.

00:18:10.410 --> 00:18:12.630
The next [inaudible] is when you
would [inaudible] the evidence

00:18:12.630 --> 00:18:15.490
that we might then hear
because they also illustrate

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:18.460
incidentally the force
of Nelson's passion.

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.110
I don't know how good
your paleography is,

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:22.400
but if you look closely
at the screen,

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:25.370
you'll see that in this excerpt
he declares his own feelings be

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:28.770
so strong that, "I
might be trusted

00:18:28.770 --> 00:18:32.540
with 50 virgins naked
in a dark room."

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:36.340
So, that's Lord Nelson.

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:38.860
He was writing this after he'd
had his hand amputated as well,

00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:41.010
so we [inaudible] as he's
dictating this to someone,

00:18:41.010 --> 00:18:44.340
which is hard to imagine, but
probably he taught himself

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:45.830
to write with his other hand.

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:49.870
So, it was a private
communication.

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:51.650
It's important to
emphasize, I think therefore

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:54.650
that the sheer variety of
papers, the Georgian Papers,

00:18:54.650 --> 00:18:56.830
is a key part of the importance.

00:18:56.830 --> 00:18:58.170
And as we might expect,
both Andrew

00:18:58.170 --> 00:18:59.870
and Jim will show you shortly,

00:18:59.870 --> 00:19:02.120
discoveries in the papers
already shed new light

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:05.270
on politics, both domestic and
international in the period,

00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:06.800
including the [inaudible]
relations of Britain

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:10.080
and the North American colonies
and then the United States.

00:19:10.080 --> 00:19:11.380
But it goes also interactions

00:19:11.380 --> 00:19:12.920
with Europe during
the revolutionary

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:14.790
and Napoleonic Wars
and with other parts

00:19:14.790 --> 00:19:17.290
of the British Empire and
beyond, the Macartney mission

00:19:17.290 --> 00:19:19.880
to China for example
being one of those.

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:21.400
And these are the
kind of revelations

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:24.840
that we might all expect
from the monarchs' papers.

00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:26.490
But there's a lot
more to it than that.

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:29.210
And this pie chart, which
is a work in progress,

00:19:29.210 --> 00:19:31.230
it changes every time I see it.

00:19:31.230 --> 00:19:33.080
It tries to analyze
what we've got

00:19:33.080 --> 00:19:37.290
in these papers in
breaking it down.

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:38.590
And anyone who is good

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:40.730
at taxonomy will instantly see
these are not a coherent set

00:19:40.730 --> 00:19:43.250
of categories because we
have some personal names

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:45.460
of the [inaudible] themes
and therefore all kinds

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:46.980
of overlaps are taking
place here

00:19:46.980 --> 00:19:49.250
within those broad
sways that's labeled

00:19:49.250 --> 00:19:52.090
with a particular
monarch's name.

00:19:52.090 --> 00:19:54.400
But even allowing for
all its weaknesses,

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:57.850
this does give you a sense of
the sheer variety of papers

00:19:57.850 --> 00:20:00.380
which are in the documents
even before you take account

00:20:00.380 --> 00:20:04.250
of the variety hidden behind
those monarchs' names.

00:20:04.250 --> 00:20:06.560
There's lot here, for example,
the historian of science

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:10.460
and medicine manifest-- we know

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:13.590
after that George III was
famously ill for a long time

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:15.630
and awful lots of records
relating to the treatment

00:20:15.630 --> 00:20:19.850
and diagnosis of that illness
and that often painful reading,

00:20:19.850 --> 00:20:22.370
stuff relating to his
interest in scientific inquiry,

00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:23.740
relating to a magnificent
collection

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:26.180
of scientific instruments that
my university is not fortunate

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:28.090
to own but you can see
through our kindness

00:20:28.090 --> 00:20:29.620
in the science museum
where they were on display,

00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:32.960
a magnificent collection
of telescopes

00:20:32.960 --> 00:20:34.700
and [inaudible] and so on.

00:20:34.700 --> 00:20:37.440
But you'll also get the emphasis
with the other family members

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:39.630
and they suffer from
distress in large variety

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:43.080
of illnesses between--
across the range of them.

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:46.250
And you'll find also lots of
stuff in their emotional lives,

00:20:46.250 --> 00:20:47.660
of all these princes

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:51.250
and princesses often very
complex relationships often

00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:52.550
ending tragically.

00:20:52.550 --> 00:20:54.190
And again, anyone with an
interest in the history

00:20:54.190 --> 00:20:56.370
of interpersonal
relations or gender history

00:20:56.370 --> 00:21:00.670
from the people find awful lot
of [inaudible] material here.

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:02.350
Then there were papers
relating to the workings

00:21:02.350 --> 00:21:04.580
of the royal households,
the knots and bolts

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:08.790
of keeping the show on the road
in terms of food, provisioning,

00:21:08.790 --> 00:21:12.210
equipping the buildings
with objects, and so on.

00:21:12.210 --> 00:21:15.630
And that's another very rich
dimension of the collection

00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:20.110
which we only just began to
think about historians of art,

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:22.930
the book, or maps,
we'll find documents

00:21:22.930 --> 00:21:24.230
that are absolutely vital

00:21:24.230 --> 00:21:25.590
to interpreting magnificent
collections

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:27.950
of those objects held by the
British Library and at Windsor

00:21:27.950 --> 00:21:29.390
and anyone who's
had a chance to look

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:31.360
at the map collection
of George III.

00:21:31.360 --> 00:21:33.360
It's an absolute
fantastic resource.

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.510
If you didn't travel, this
was how he knew the world.

00:21:35.510 --> 00:21:37.070
He looked at the
maps and pictures.

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:39.410
And that's how he understood
the world around him.

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:44.170
And of course the [inaudible]
because they bought lots

00:21:44.170 --> 00:21:46.620
and lots of stuff, lots
of really important

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:50.390
for art historians you could
do an awful lot of these lined

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:52.850
up against the libraries
collections or against those

00:21:52.850 --> 00:21:54.150
in the British Library.

00:21:54.150 --> 00:21:56.050
Commissioning buildings,
commissioning paintings,

00:21:56.050 --> 00:21:58.820
commissioning music,
handle festivals, right,

00:21:58.820 --> 00:22:00.120
a part of George III's life.

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:05.050
So, something for everybody
is the basic message

00:22:05.050 --> 00:22:07.060
and exploring the
papers we'll find a lot

00:22:07.060 --> 00:22:09.440
about English monarchy
but also about societies

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:12.500
in which the monarchs lived
and also the societies

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:16.120
in which they didn't
live, those overseas

00:22:16.120 --> 00:22:18.350
in which [inaudible] to rule.

00:22:18.350 --> 00:22:20.580
And most-- many of the
papers I think which relate

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.220
to the less person
[inaudible] the monarch

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:24.010
of those we know
the least about.

00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:26.800
And as we move into those,
I think it's very hard

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:28.740
to predict what we
find but there is going

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:31.690
to be some major new
agendas I think set

00:22:31.690 --> 00:22:35.620
for researchers very
rapidly as we explore those.

00:22:35.620 --> 00:22:38.510
That said even where we've
had papers that's already been

00:22:38.510 --> 00:22:41.200
published, the program
is shedding new light.

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:44.590
And we can see for example,
where editions mistook

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:47.820
or omitted or misinterpreted.

00:22:47.820 --> 00:22:49.370
And it's very striking
for example

00:22:49.370 --> 00:22:52.220
that the very first
volume of published letters

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:55.580
of George III came out in
the 1920s by the librarian,

00:22:55.580 --> 00:23:00.120
since then he produced a very
thick volume of correspondents.

00:23:00.120 --> 00:23:03.160
One of his colleagues was
so outraged by the quality

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:05.830
of this edition that he then
published the hardback edition

00:23:05.830 --> 00:23:09.500
of corrections to that
volume, to volume one

00:23:09.500 --> 00:23:11.870
that was 100 pages long.

00:23:11.870 --> 00:23:14.680
And yet that's the collection
we still have to work with.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:16.700
So, we're going to put
these digitized images,

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:20.170
we're going to be looking
at those documents and new.

00:23:20.170 --> 00:23:23.120
But also of course when you look
at the document in manuscript

00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:24.480
or in the very high
quality digital

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:26.140
and if you see something
quite different

00:23:26.140 --> 00:23:27.760
from when you look
at the printed page.

00:23:27.760 --> 00:23:30.300
If you look at George
III's abdication letters

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:33.850
when he's drafting this
potential abdication speech,

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:36.160
he thinks he might need to
give shortly after the loss

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:37.460
of the American colonies.

00:23:37.460 --> 00:23:39.600
It's one thing to read
the finished version.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.800
But you look at the original

00:23:41.800 --> 00:23:44.100
and you see the agonized
crossings out.

00:23:44.100 --> 00:23:47.150
You see the rethinking
that's going on,

00:23:47.150 --> 00:23:50.030
something about the
psychological state of mind

00:23:50.030 --> 00:23:52.680
that comes across
[inaudible] in that form

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:54.930
that simply could not be
reproduced even if you try

00:23:54.930 --> 00:24:00.250
to annotate a printed edition to
indicate all those corrections.

00:24:00.250 --> 00:24:03.580
And I think we look at them
fresh again, if we're looking

00:24:03.580 --> 00:24:05.730
at them as a document
rather than as part

00:24:05.730 --> 00:24:07.030
of a narrative history

00:24:07.030 --> 00:24:09.240
where maybe this is
reproduced as a part of a story.

00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:12.190
And we know that he thought
of that abdication and we know

00:24:12.190 --> 00:24:14.700
that it's part of the story
of George is agonizing

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:17.540
after the end of
the American war.

00:24:17.540 --> 00:24:19.190
But nobody has ever
reported to say, well,

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:21.170
where did you get the
idea of abdicating from?

00:24:21.170 --> 00:24:24.110
Because after all, this is was a
king who is very, very conscious

00:24:24.110 --> 00:24:28.690
of being a divinely authorized
and responsible person

00:24:28.690 --> 00:24:31.710
for his people, and yet here
he is starting to walk away,

00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:35.380
walk away at the
moment when he knows

00:24:35.380 --> 00:24:37.760
that this is a [inaudible]
no respect whatsoever

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:39.060
as potential monarch.

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:42.610
So how does he think this is an
exercise of his responsibilities

00:24:42.610 --> 00:24:44.370
to his maker if he's doing that?

00:24:44.370 --> 00:24:47.630
So we can rethink the questions
we ask about these documents,

00:24:47.630 --> 00:24:51.400
I think, as we see
them as documents.

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:54.120
Another way we see [inaudible]
part of bigger collection,

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:56.420
because the proximity of
all these different themes

00:24:56.420 --> 00:24:58.960
in one collection reflects
the very real proximity

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:03.750
of a monarchy where you
have a small court operating

00:25:03.750 --> 00:25:07.800
in a very intimate setting
with politicians and princesses

00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:12.850
and coaches and servants all in
a very limited particular space

00:25:12.850 --> 00:25:14.850
and of course all at
the heart of London,

00:25:14.850 --> 00:25:19.360
the leading world city
of the late 18th century.

00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:21.820
We could therefore have to
think quite harder what the

00:25:21.820 --> 00:25:24.640
interconnections are
among with those papers.

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:26.210
And that takes me into the
final we're going to talk

00:25:26.210 --> 00:25:29.730
about which is how we then
add value to these images

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:33.510
into the collection of
objects we're making public.

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:36.450
And there is a fantastic
program of research that's going

00:25:36.450 --> 00:25:39.180
on in association
with this program.

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:41.390
Thanks to King's and
the Omohundro Institute

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:43.600
and the generosity of our
associates at Mount Vernon

00:25:43.600 --> 00:25:45.180
and the Sons of the
American Revolution

00:25:45.180 --> 00:25:47.780
which we're enormously grateful,
now joined by the Library

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:49.630
of Congress if you heard more

00:25:49.630 --> 00:25:52.270
than 35 scholars have already
been actively researching the

00:25:52.270 --> 00:25:55.470
Georgian Papers as Georgian
Papers fellows exploring the

00:25:55.470 --> 00:26:00.410
range of themes which match the
diversity of the archive itself.

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:02.730
A particular relevance
this afternoon for example,

00:26:02.730 --> 00:26:05.580
we should note that the
Omohundro alone has now funded

00:26:05.580 --> 00:26:07.860
more than a dozen scholars
working on an American

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:10.270
or Atlantic world
topics in this program.

00:26:10.270 --> 00:26:12.450
And that's fantastic feature.

00:26:12.450 --> 00:26:15.640
And for me, it's been terrific
because I'm a really bad example

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:17.350
to kind of put a historian
who doesn't ever look

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:21.840
up to other places doing my work
and having to work alongside

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:23.890
so many people working
in American themes

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:26.870
such as illuminated so many
things I just wouldn't have got

00:26:26.870 --> 00:26:28.310
to without this program.

00:26:28.310 --> 00:26:31.210
And I think that's true of
a lot of British historians.

00:26:31.210 --> 00:26:33.540
There's something special I
think as well about having

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:37.410
so many people who can feedback
into the cataloging process

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:40.220
because that's going to help us
improve the means back to others

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:41.520
because we're thinking

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:43.040
about what these documents
are all the time the scholars

00:26:43.040 --> 00:26:44.340
as well.

00:26:44.340 --> 00:26:47.570
And also the fact we were
working on one archive.

00:26:47.570 --> 00:26:50.910
And that for me says a really
special about this program.

00:26:50.910 --> 00:26:53.200
Quite often I go to campuses
and the biggest difference

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:55.610
between me and the other people
there is we don't use the same

00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:58.850
stuff and so we can't
find an easy common ground

00:26:58.850 --> 00:27:00.210
on which to debate things.

00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:02.930
Here we have a load of scholars
doing extraordinary different

00:27:02.930 --> 00:27:04.980
things who've all been
physically working

00:27:04.980 --> 00:27:06.700
on the same papers.

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:09.040
And we had a marvelous meeting
this September organized

00:27:09.040 --> 00:27:13.300
by Omohundro where we brought
together 14 or 15 of the people

00:27:13.300 --> 00:27:15.290
who already done work
to get papers and a lot

00:27:15.290 --> 00:27:17.090
of the others came as well.

00:27:17.090 --> 00:27:21.110
And the connections the people
were making of animal history

00:27:21.110 --> 00:27:24.120
through to the highest
politics you can imagine

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:28.590
through the history of food
and the dining traditions

00:27:28.590 --> 00:27:30.570
of the monarchy, the points

00:27:30.570 --> 00:27:33.220
of sparking going off
suggesting people that you think

00:27:33.220 --> 00:27:35.200
about new dimensions
[inaudible] research

00:27:35.200 --> 00:27:38.180
on that context was
really wonderful.

00:27:38.180 --> 00:27:40.570
And I really do think that's
going to be a big feature

00:27:40.570 --> 00:27:42.740
to the program as we go forward
is that we accumulate more

00:27:42.740 --> 00:27:44.790
and more of these fellows.

00:27:44.790 --> 00:27:48.080
And indeed, we're now-- as we've
gone digital, as we have more

00:27:48.080 --> 00:27:51.070
and more documents online,
that community doesn't have

00:27:51.070 --> 00:27:53.390
to be just [inaudible], we
can have a digital community.

00:27:53.390 --> 00:27:56.340
Two weeks ago, we
launched, The King's Friend,

00:27:56.340 --> 00:27:59.320
which is online network
research to see opportunities

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:01.500
to advance the work
through the papers program.

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:05.140
And already more than 220
scholars joined that network.

00:28:05.140 --> 00:28:07.640
About a third of those
were in the United States

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:10.550
but they're worldwide and they
come from department of history,

00:28:10.550 --> 00:28:14.520
of literature, of art, of
music, and lots of curators

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:16.110
and archivists as well.

00:28:16.110 --> 00:28:17.810
And then we're going to
be keeping them involved

00:28:17.810 --> 00:28:19.290
with the project
as it goes forward,

00:28:19.290 --> 00:28:21.120
having to give them advance
opportunities to look

00:28:21.120 --> 00:28:22.720
at materials before
it goes public

00:28:22.720 --> 00:28:24.900
so they can contribute the
interpretations for us.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:27.490
It's a new approach to try to
bind people to approach you

00:28:27.490 --> 00:28:29.550
like this, one which we
are really excited about,

00:28:29.550 --> 00:28:30.850
which we hope will
feed into things

00:28:30.850 --> 00:28:34.370
like the exhibitions we've been
hearing about as we go forward.

00:28:34.370 --> 00:28:36.500
And of course the digital lets
you do is potentially make

00:28:36.500 --> 00:28:39.180
relations with other archives
and put documents together

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:41.050
which you wouldn't always
be able to do physically.

00:28:41.050 --> 00:28:43.940
And we hope to try and do some
of that with making connections

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:46.270
to other archives
online, particularly those

00:28:46.270 --> 00:28:48.410
that are endangered, say those
in Jamaica or other places

00:28:48.410 --> 00:28:51.000
where we might be able to make
connections with them and try

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.310
and do something together.

00:28:53.310 --> 00:28:56.020
Another [inaudible] see
transcription going forward

00:28:56.020 --> 00:28:57.440
with students, scholars,

00:28:57.440 --> 00:28:59.670
and wide [inaudible] public
taking part in the act

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:04.010
to practice transcription and in
the interpretation of documents.

00:29:04.010 --> 00:29:05.440
And already both
William and Mary

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:07.070
and King's both postgraduate

00:29:07.070 --> 00:29:10.280
and undergraduate students have
the opportunity to get involved

00:29:10.280 --> 00:29:12.930
in this project at first hand.

00:29:12.930 --> 00:29:15.230
My own students at
King's selected each

00:29:15.230 --> 00:29:16.880
of the document at random.

00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:18.610
They would give them a free
choice to go to the archive

00:29:18.610 --> 00:29:20.360
and find some things
that's both to them

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:22.110
and then they were
given 10 weeks

00:29:22.110 --> 00:29:25.320
to produce an online digital
edition of that document.

00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:26.970
And they came from all
kinds of disciplines.

00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:28.570
So one of favorites
was a math student

00:29:28.570 --> 00:29:30.670
who never had done any
history before and they went

00:29:30.670 --> 00:29:33.460
into George's exercise books
as a young man and say,

00:29:33.460 --> 00:29:34.760
what math is he doing?

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:36.160
Where is he getting
that math from?

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:38.320
And they identified
the textbooks he used.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:41.170
Why he was doing this math,
is all about ballistics

00:29:41.170 --> 00:29:42.840
so he could picture, you know,

00:29:42.840 --> 00:29:45.460
the cannonballs landed
in the right place.

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:48.160
But no, it's a fantastic thing
for her to do to take ownership

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:50.530
of this, her own project
and we'll feed that back

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:53.730
into the archive project
because we didn't know this.

00:29:53.730 --> 00:29:55.030
That student founded that

00:29:55.030 --> 00:29:56.620
and that would be her
contribution to the project.

00:29:56.620 --> 00:30:00.050
So that's a great thing I think,
putting research into the heart

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:02.040
of student's education.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:03.340
We're next taking it schools.

00:30:03.340 --> 00:30:05.960
I'm talking to the British
Historical Association building

00:30:05.960 --> 00:30:08.250
a collection of documents will
be used in school when teaching

00:30:08.250 --> 00:30:12.300
for [inaudible] school children
due the [inaudible] using

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:14.380
Georgian Papers to
illuminate the curriculum.

00:30:14.380 --> 00:30:17.400
Not just about George III
but about literacy and things

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:19.840
as part of the school
curriculum.

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:23.320
So, all of those things
speak to what I found is

00:30:23.320 --> 00:30:25.540
that digital was doing
the last 20 years.

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:27.160
It's an extraordinary
moment for us

00:30:27.160 --> 00:30:29.400
that we can take our
serious scholarly work

00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:31.740
without compromising
it in terms of rigor

00:30:31.740 --> 00:30:33.550
or scholarship find
point connection

00:30:33.550 --> 00:30:36.640
with the wider historical
public and work together to try

00:30:36.640 --> 00:30:38.780
and improve and enhance
our interpretation.

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:40.580
It's a wonderful
thing to be able to do

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:43.100
and the Georgian Papers
project offers a possibility

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:44.790
of doing this with a
new set of documents

00:30:44.790 --> 00:30:46.590
on a different scale
and internationally.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:49.880
And that's just fantastic
I think for me.

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:52.590
That said, the work
professional scholars will be

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:53.970
at the core what
we're going to do

00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:55.380
as you would like
to hear, folks.

00:30:55.380 --> 00:30:58.180
And period we're dealing
with obviously is a complex

00:30:58.180 --> 00:31:01.080
and extraordinary one
exhibiting both parallels

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:02.710
with their own time
and you can think

00:31:02.710 --> 00:31:05.940
of the globalization
shifting political tectonics

00:31:05.940 --> 00:31:08.280
that leave people wrong-footed
at every moment to what

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:11.480
to do next or how to act,
the impact in new media

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:14.000
like a very striking parallel
between the politics there

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:18.830
and now and rapidly evolving
social economic challenges.

00:31:18.830 --> 00:31:21.460
There's also striking contrast,
we see the origins of many

00:31:21.460 --> 00:31:23.920
of our contemporary
institutions and practices

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:26.060
and with very different
circumstances

00:31:26.060 --> 00:31:27.360
in which they now operate.

00:31:27.360 --> 00:31:30.130
And to make sense, that's
going to require a lot of skill

00:31:30.130 --> 00:31:32.810
and patience and research as
well as a lot of foreknowledge

00:31:32.810 --> 00:31:34.420
so we will need professional
historians.

00:31:34.420 --> 00:31:37.970
So it's pleasure to be able to
hand over to three such scholars

00:31:37.970 --> 00:31:40.230
who all got patience
and foreknowledge

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:43.010
and they will continue our
discussion by explaining some

00:31:43.010 --> 00:31:44.430
of the themes that's researched

00:31:44.430 --> 00:31:46.150
in the papers is
already highlighting.

00:31:46.150 --> 00:31:47.450
Thank you very much.

00:31:47.450 --> 00:31:49.750
