00:33:01.750 --> 00:33:05.410
of being the first
Omohundro fellow to be

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:07.200
in the Georgian archive.

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:10.560
I beat my fellow over
there by about a month.

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:13.190
So now I'm giving a talk
in the Library of Congress.

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:14.870
I'm not sure it's going
to get any better so I'd

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:17.130
like to announce my
retirement at the conclusion

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:19.690
of today's program [laughter].

00:33:19.690 --> 00:33:23.360
I wanted-- I'd like to tell
you about my time in Windsor

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:25.270
and a bit about my
research there

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:28.250
by telling you a
story about two men.

00:33:28.250 --> 00:33:32.350
Admiral Sir Samuel Hood
and General Jacob De Bude.

00:33:32.350 --> 00:33:34.660
These are common household
names in the history

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:37.470
of the American Revolution
although it's entirely possible

00:33:37.470 --> 00:33:40.250
and you probably have
heard of Lord Hood.

00:33:40.250 --> 00:33:43.710
But they shared a correspondence
during a critical period

00:33:43.710 --> 00:33:45.500
of the American warfare
independence.

00:33:45.500 --> 00:33:47.490
Letters that I found locked away

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:50.580
in the royal archives
of Windsor Castle.

00:33:50.580 --> 00:33:53.610
By necessity, then this story
begins not of the 18th century

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:56.830
but on the 21st on a
cool September morning,

00:33:56.830 --> 00:33:59.390
two years ago in
the round tower.

00:33:59.390 --> 00:34:01.900
I applied for my Georgian
Papers fellowship hoping

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:04.750
to find material for
my dissertation project

00:34:04.750 --> 00:34:07.930
which was a study of Scottish
immigration to North America

00:34:07.930 --> 00:34:09.750
in the era of the
American Revolution.

00:34:09.750 --> 00:34:14.150
And I found that other
evidence in some archives

00:34:14.150 --> 00:34:17.820
that George III was aware what
some amongst the Scottish elite

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:21.910
described as a depopulation
crisis in Scotland.

00:34:21.910 --> 00:34:25.210
In other words they believed
that a combination of factors

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:27.500
that push Scots out of
Scotland and pull them

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:31.070
to the colonies here would
deprive Britain of laborers

00:34:31.070 --> 00:34:35.680
and soldiers at a critical
moment in the imperial crisis.

00:34:35.680 --> 00:34:38.430
And so as I waited
through boxes of material

00:34:38.430 --> 00:34:41.940
on the royal archives,
seeking answer to my questions,

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:45.770
I ask to see the papers
of General Jacob de Bude,

00:34:45.770 --> 00:34:48.550
the man so honored here
by this inscription

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:51.070
within Saint George's
chapel located just

00:34:51.070 --> 00:34:53.600
down the hill from
the round tower.

00:34:53.600 --> 00:34:56.860
Born in Geneva in the early
18th century, as a younger man,

00:34:56.860 --> 00:34:58.510
de Bude acted as a military page

00:34:58.510 --> 00:35:02.460
for George III's great uncle
William, Prince of Orange.

00:35:02.460 --> 00:35:05.710
He later served in
a Swiss regimen.

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:09.330
In 1772, de Bude joined
the British royal household

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:10.650
to oversee the education

00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:13.220
of the princes William
Henry and Edward.

00:35:13.220 --> 00:35:15.880
George III made him a
general in the Hanoverian army

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:19.460
and apparently became
the king's aide-de-camp.

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:21.910
He later served as Prince
Frederick's secretary

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:24.760
and it was Frederick who
placed memorial to de Bude

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:26.450
in St. George's Chapel,

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:30.550
a testimony to that man's long
service to the royal family.

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:34.340
And so on that September
morning, in 2015,

00:35:34.340 --> 00:35:37.930
I received a red archival box
similar to what Arthur showed

00:35:37.930 --> 00:35:41.400
in the video there containing de
Bude's papers hoping upon hope

00:35:41.400 --> 00:35:43.090
that they pour something
directly

00:35:43.090 --> 00:35:45.980
on my dissertation topic
hoping that I find a letter

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:48.880
from the king where he's
talking to de Bude in confidence

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:51.640
about this potential crisis.

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:55.800
And I didn't find
anything, but that's OK.

00:35:55.800 --> 00:35:58.390
And part of the process of
this program is to figure

00:35:58.390 --> 00:36:01.150
out what is there and
what is not there.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:03.850
And as I'd like to say,
what I found is better

00:36:03.850 --> 00:36:07.990
in more instances that one,
and so in that box sandwiched

00:36:07.990 --> 00:36:11.710
between account books and
a collection of recipes.

00:36:11.710 --> 00:36:15.000
So if you need anything for
the holidays, let me know.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.990
I found a catch of letters
wrapped in brown paper

00:36:17.990 --> 00:36:21.130
and bound together
by a piece of string.

00:36:21.130 --> 00:36:22.770
Opening that package
I discovered

00:36:22.770 --> 00:36:26.660
about 140 letters plus
enclosures written

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:30.110
to de Bude from Admiral Hood.

00:36:30.110 --> 00:36:35.100
Here was a collection unknown
to scholars, dating between 1781

00:36:35.100 --> 00:36:39.810
and 1783, written by one of
Britain's senior naval officers

00:36:39.810 --> 00:36:43.300
to one of George III's
trusted men in the last years

00:36:43.300 --> 00:36:44.600
of the revolutionary war.

00:36:44.600 --> 00:36:49.260
I wonder what it could mean
that these letters existed

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:53.140
in this collection within
this particular archive

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:55.470
and what they might tell
us about the relationship

00:36:55.470 --> 00:36:59.020
between these two men, about
the American Revolution

00:36:59.020 --> 00:37:01.760
and about George III.

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:03.540
To begin to answer
those questions,

00:37:03.540 --> 00:37:04.840
we need to know something

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:09.190
about de Bude's correspondent,
Admiral Hood.

00:37:09.190 --> 00:37:11.850
A season naval veteran,
Hood first went to see

00:37:11.850 --> 00:37:14.500
with the royal navy
in the 1740s.

00:37:14.500 --> 00:37:16.050
Served in a seven years war,

00:37:16.050 --> 00:37:18.500
what we commonly called
the French-Indian war

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:21.210
in North America,
stationed in Halifax,

00:37:21.210 --> 00:37:24.810
Nova Scotia in the years
before the American Revolution,

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:26.620
served as a commissioner
of the naval yards

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:28.460
at Portsmouth, England.

00:37:28.460 --> 00:37:30.740
Before becoming a flag
officer in the British fleet

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:35.240
in the early 1780s, confident
in his own abilities,

00:37:35.240 --> 00:37:38.820
often to the point of arrogance,
Hood all too easily found fault

00:37:38.820 --> 00:37:42.890
in the conduct of his fellow
officers, even his superiors.

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:46.060
He was not afraid to express
his opinions to his friends

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:50.380
and to his civilian superiors
and the luminous correspondents.

00:37:50.380 --> 00:37:52.930
But it was never without a
point and that's important,

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:55.960
Hood wanted his correspondents
to understand

00:37:55.960 --> 00:38:00.110
where the officers had gone
wrong, wanted to expose flaws

00:38:00.110 --> 00:38:03.210
in British military strategy
and wanted to offer a sense

00:38:03.210 --> 00:38:07.090
of the potential consequences
of certain military choices.

00:38:07.090 --> 00:38:09.400
Now of course, you know,
Hood, he's not writing this

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:12.730
without an eye towards his own
conduct, his own reputation.

00:38:12.730 --> 00:38:16.150
He wants his correspondents
to hold him in high regard.

00:38:16.150 --> 00:38:17.930
But he generally believed
in the righteousness

00:38:17.930 --> 00:38:19.230
of the British cause

00:38:19.230 --> 00:38:20.880
in suppressing the
American rebellion.

00:38:20.880 --> 00:38:26.440
He was content on doing his duty
to king, country, and empire.

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:29.310
And he was also a
politically astute man.

00:38:29.310 --> 00:38:31.570
He was well versed
in 18th century ideas

00:38:31.570 --> 00:38:34.020
of duty, honor, and propriety.

00:38:34.020 --> 00:38:36.390
While he was on friendly
terms with the king,

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:38.280
Hood dared not flout
the chain of command

00:38:38.280 --> 00:38:41.650
and send his grievances
directly to George III.

00:38:41.650 --> 00:38:44.410
And so with that in mind, I
want to emphasize the importance

00:38:44.410 --> 00:38:47.650
of to whom Hood is writing.

00:38:47.650 --> 00:38:49.520
True, some of what Hood wrote

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:52.270
to de Bude mirrored what
he communicated to others.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:55.820
But the fact that he provided
de Bude one of the king's men

00:38:55.820 --> 00:38:57.500
with detailed accounts
of the war effort

00:38:57.500 --> 00:39:00.280
and the people involved
raises [inaudible] prospect

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:03.620
that Hood saw these letters
as way to back-channel

00:39:03.620 --> 00:39:06.340
to George III himself.

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:09.260
Hood's correspondence with
de Bude written in the wake

00:39:09.260 --> 00:39:12.980
of a catastrophic British defeat
in the late summer of 1781,

00:39:12.980 --> 00:39:14.900
offers an excellent
example of the kind

00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:18.420
of information he might have
conveyed to this exchange.

00:39:18.420 --> 00:39:22.390
They help illuminate a fatal
moment and the people involved

00:39:22.390 --> 00:39:24.310
in Britain's efforts to
subdue the rebellion.

00:39:24.310 --> 00:39:27.680
And so most of us are aware
I think with the Battle

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:31.250
of Yorktown of October 1781,

00:39:31.250 --> 00:39:33.880
the victory by the combined
Franco-American army

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:38.940
that traps Cornwallis southern
Army on New York peninsula

00:39:38.940 --> 00:39:42.720
and leads to peace
negotiation with the Americans.

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:45.020
Certainly if you're familiar
with the Hamilton's soundtrack,

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:48.330
you know this by heart
by now [laughter].

00:39:48.330 --> 00:39:52.260
Far fewer know much about
the Battle of the Chesapeake,

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:56.440
just one month before on
September the 5th, 1781.

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:58.140
This was the decisive
naval engagement

00:39:58.140 --> 00:39:59.830
of the American Revolution,

00:39:59.830 --> 00:40:02.720
especially with respect
securing American independence.

00:40:02.720 --> 00:40:05.220
It is difficult to imagine
Cornwallis' surrender

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:07.050
without it.

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:10.360
The clash of the Virginia coast
was a reflection of Britain's--

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:12.630
the British military
and southern strategy

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:14.490
in this period of a war.

00:40:14.490 --> 00:40:18.560
After John Burgoyne's
surrender at Saratoga in 1777

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:21.610
and France's formal entry into
the war the following year,

00:40:21.610 --> 00:40:23.610
the British military
concentrated its efforts

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:26.390
in the southern colonies,
partly in the belief and not

00:40:26.390 --> 00:40:29.280
without good reason that they
would find greater numbers

00:40:29.280 --> 00:40:32.160
of loyal Americans in the south.

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:34.590
In for a time, the
British found success.

00:40:34.590 --> 00:40:37.740
They actually re-conquered
Georgia in the fall of 1779.

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:40.660
That colony is declared at
the king's peace, all right?

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:41.980
So that's one check mark.

00:40:41.980 --> 00:40:45.020
In May 1780, they captured
Charles Town, South Carolina,

00:40:45.020 --> 00:40:46.670
all right, captured one

00:40:46.670 --> 00:40:49.690
of the southern coast's
most important ports.

00:40:49.690 --> 00:40:52.280
And after Charles Town
falls into British hands,

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:54.700
Lord Cornwallis takes
command of the southern army,

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:57.500
spends the better part of the
next year and a half working

00:40:57.500 --> 00:41:01.370
to pacify South Carolina where
a very violent civil war breaks

00:41:01.370 --> 00:41:04.890
out between patriot and
loyalist, moving north

00:41:04.890 --> 00:41:08.240
into North Carolina and
finally into Virginia.

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:11.220
And in Virginia, he has orders
from General Sir Henry Clinton

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:14.140
to establish a fortified
position near a port

00:41:14.140 --> 00:41:16.960
to which the British
could send supplies.

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:18.770
And all the while,
American continental

00:41:18.770 --> 00:41:22.650
and militia forces are
harassing him and his men.

00:41:22.650 --> 00:41:26.240
By the summer of 1781,
George Washington

00:41:26.240 --> 00:41:29.150
and de Rochambeau
sense an opportunity.

00:41:29.150 --> 00:41:31.500
Stationed up the Hudson River
near White Plains, New York,

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:33.440
the two generals debated
whether to launch a strike

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:35.710
against the British
headquarters in New York City,

00:41:35.710 --> 00:41:38.640
a city that the British
[inaudible] of the war

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:41.330
or to begin an offensive
in Virginia to capture

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:43.490
or destroy Cornwallis'
southern army.

00:41:43.490 --> 00:41:47.270
And ultimately they
choose Virginia largely

00:41:47.270 --> 00:41:50.650
because Rochambeau convinces
Washington who really wants

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:52.830
to just go in there and get
the crap out of the British

00:41:52.830 --> 00:41:56.750
in New York that Virginia
is the better option.

00:41:56.750 --> 00:41:59.530
But with the British Navy
patrolling American waters,

00:41:59.530 --> 00:42:01.660
Washington and Rochambeau
needed the assistance

00:42:01.660 --> 00:42:04.890
of the French fleet to
accomplish their objectives.

00:42:04.890 --> 00:42:08.130
One small French naval force lay
off Rhode Island while another

00:42:08.130 --> 00:42:10.480
under the command of Admiral
de Grasse was soon expected

00:42:10.480 --> 00:42:11.950
on the West Indies.

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:14.500
If you'd like to know more
about the American Revolution

00:42:14.500 --> 00:42:15.910
in the Caribbean,
I encourage you

00:42:15.910 --> 00:42:18.790
to read Andrew O'Shaughnessy's
book "An Empire Divided".

00:42:18.790 --> 00:42:20.100
It's terrific.

00:42:20.100 --> 00:42:22.380
Go pick up your copy today.

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:25.780
And once that fleet arrives,
Rochambeau sends a message

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:28.490
to de Grasse asking him
to bring his fleet north

00:42:28.490 --> 00:42:32.290
to assist the allied armies
marching toward Virginia.

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.810
The British had a fleet in
the West Indies as well,

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:37.860
one that included Hood
abort his flagship.

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:40.250
And the British rightly
suspected

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:42.630
that their enemies were
preparing a joint operation

00:42:42.630 --> 00:42:45.290
either against General
Clinton's forces in New York

00:42:45.290 --> 00:42:48.730
or against Lord Cornwallis
in Virginia.

00:42:48.730 --> 00:42:50.450
The senior British
admiral ordered Hood

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:54.690
to take a detachment of 14 ships
of the lines to the battleships

00:42:54.690 --> 00:42:57.350
to track de Grasse after the
French commander began the

00:42:57.350 --> 00:42:58.800
voyage north.

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:02.020
Because Hood took a more direct
route to the American mainland,

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:03.890
he actually passes
de Grasse and arrives

00:43:03.890 --> 00:43:08.280
in Chesapeake Bay
on August 25, 1781.

00:43:08.280 --> 00:43:11.240
Finding no French ships in
the bay, Hood sailed north

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:13.970
to New York City to
consult with Admiral Graves

00:43:13.970 --> 00:43:15.660
who had the overall command
with the British fleet

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:17.820
in North America at this time.

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:21.690
And when Hood, Graves, and other
officers observed the sailing

00:43:21.690 --> 00:43:24.550
of the French fleet at Rhode
Island, they correctly suspected

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:26.570
that Virginia was the target.

00:43:26.570 --> 00:43:29.900
Mobilizing a combined fleet
of 19 ships of the line,

00:43:29.900 --> 00:43:32.390
the British sailed south
to prevent the French

00:43:32.390 --> 00:43:35.210
from isolating Cornwallis' army.

00:43:35.210 --> 00:43:39.710
And here you have a map from
the Library of Congress,

00:43:39.710 --> 00:43:41.370
depicting this battle.

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:42.880
And the British fleet is--

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:46.480
are the darker of
the two colors there.

00:43:46.480 --> 00:43:49.910
On September the 5th, 1781,
Hood, Graves, and the rest

00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:52.590
of the British fleet encountered
de Grasse and his force

00:43:52.590 --> 00:43:56.120
of 24 ships of the line near
the mouth of Chesapeake Bay.

00:43:56.120 --> 00:43:58.990
Outnumbered, outgunned,
outmanned,

00:43:58.990 --> 00:44:01.650
the British nevertheless
put up a decent fight

00:44:01.650 --> 00:44:05.410
for a few hours before
being forced to withdraw.

00:44:05.410 --> 00:44:07.570
De Grasse's victory
left the French

00:44:07.570 --> 00:44:09.350
in command of Virginia waters.

00:44:09.350 --> 00:44:13.420
Tracking Cornwallis on land
has the Franco-American army

00:44:13.420 --> 00:44:15.090
drew near.

00:44:15.090 --> 00:44:17.610
Despite the magnitude
of this defeat,

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:20.420
Admiral Hood was
not lost for words.

00:44:20.420 --> 00:44:21.720
He sent letters

00:44:21.720 --> 00:44:24.300
to correspondents
including Jacob de Bude,

00:44:24.300 --> 00:44:27.340
describing the battle in what he
thought it meant for the faith

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:29.510
of Britain's American empire.

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:33.620
He composed a long letter to de
Bude 11 days after the battle,

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:37.230
in which he noted, "On
the 5th instant, at 11 am,

00:44:37.230 --> 00:44:40.380
we plainly discovered 24 sail
of French ships of the line

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:43.660
and two frigates at
anchor about Lynnhaven Bay,

00:44:43.660 --> 00:44:46.050
which afforded the British
fleet a most glorious opening

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:48.270
for making a close
attack to advantage

00:44:48.270 --> 00:44:50.590
but it was not embraced.

00:44:50.590 --> 00:44:54.990
But with this letter,
Hood also included a copy

00:44:54.990 --> 00:44:59.520
of his thoughts composed on
the morning after the battle.

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:02.600
Although uncharacteristically
short nevertheless,

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:04.240
Hood was characteristically
blunt

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:06.020
in his assessment of the battle.

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:08.590
And this is the message
he wants to convey

00:45:08.590 --> 00:45:11.690
to his correspondents
including de Bude.

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:14.470
"Yesterday the British
fleet had a rich

00:45:14.470 --> 00:45:17.370
and most delightful harvest
of glory, presented to it,

00:45:17.370 --> 00:45:20.800
but admitted to gather it
in more instances than one."

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:24.950
And here we see a fine example
of Hood noting the failure

00:45:24.950 --> 00:45:30.580
of a superior officer's judgment
in superiority of his own.

00:45:30.580 --> 00:45:32.990
Hood argued that Admiral
Graves who commanded the center

00:45:32.990 --> 00:45:35.710
of the British line
failed to press the attack.

00:45:35.710 --> 00:45:38.040
He believed that if Graves
had exploited weak points

00:45:38.040 --> 00:45:39.980
in the French line, it
might have been able Hood

00:45:39.980 --> 00:45:42.390
to cut the French
center to pieces.

00:45:42.390 --> 00:45:47.060
But as Hood sought, Graves
failed to act decisively.

00:45:47.060 --> 00:45:49.990
In this another letters,
Hood made claim to de Bude

00:45:49.990 --> 00:45:52.370
that defeat on the
5th of September along

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:55.740
with the later decision not to
mount another rescue effort,

00:45:55.740 --> 00:45:58.380
portended doom for Lord
Cornwallis, his army,

00:45:58.380 --> 00:45:59.680
and the British war effort.

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:02.490
I found in this particular
collection, he writes letters

00:46:02.490 --> 00:46:05.660
on the 24th of September where
he describes the council of war

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:07.180
and Hood is desperately arguing

00:46:07.180 --> 00:46:10.070
that the British should send
fire ships in to French lines.

00:46:10.070 --> 00:46:12.900
Basically they would set their
own vessels on fire and ram them

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.820
into the French fleet as
a means to punch a hole

00:46:15.820 --> 00:46:18.900
to rescue Cornwallis, and he
can't convince them to do it

00:46:18.900 --> 00:46:21.600
and he is just beside himself.

00:46:21.600 --> 00:46:22.940
He's really quite passionate

00:46:22.940 --> 00:46:25.690
about what he thinks is
the right thing to do.

00:46:25.690 --> 00:46:28.500
In the intimate nature
of this correspondence

00:46:28.500 --> 00:46:30.860
between these two important
figures in the British military

00:46:30.860 --> 00:46:33.480
and in the royal household
and the implication

00:46:33.480 --> 00:46:35.850
that it may represent a
means to convey information

00:46:35.850 --> 00:46:39.310
to George III, compels
us to ask new questions

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:41.640
about various aspects of
the American Revolution.

00:46:41.640 --> 00:46:43.450
You know, in this town we

00:46:43.450 --> 00:46:45.050
like to ask what did
the president know

00:46:45.050 --> 00:46:46.400
and when did he know it.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:48.450
And we can modify that
question to ask with, well,

00:46:48.450 --> 00:46:51.130
what did the king know
and when did he know it?

00:46:51.130 --> 00:46:53.920
And so I want to leave you with
the idea that the significance

00:46:53.920 --> 00:46:57.500
of the Hood-de Bude letters
is that they are suggestive

00:46:57.500 --> 00:46:59.430
of a broader and formal
intelligence network

00:46:59.430 --> 00:47:02.570
that George III used to gather
information about the progress

00:47:02.570 --> 00:47:04.640
of the American war,
developments

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:07.630
in Europe, and matters at home.

00:47:07.630 --> 00:47:10.360
George III took his duties
as sovereign seriously

00:47:10.360 --> 00:47:13.500
as Arthur suggested, making
it a point to know as much,

00:47:13.500 --> 00:47:16.570
if not more about policy,
politics, and military strategy

00:47:16.570 --> 00:47:21.480
as the ministers who ran his
government and his empire.

00:47:21.480 --> 00:47:24.120
And for a king who gave his
last full measure of devotion

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:27.240
to the preservation of that
empire and whose ministers had

00:47:27.240 --> 00:47:29.220
to drag him to the conclusion

00:47:29.220 --> 00:47:32.180
that Britain could not win
this imperial civil war,

00:47:32.180 --> 00:47:33.480
letters such as these along

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:35.940
with other evidence can give
us a new window not only

00:47:35.940 --> 00:47:38.520
into naval history,
military history,

00:47:38.520 --> 00:47:41.790
but also into the king's mind.

00:47:41.790 --> 00:47:43.590
The letters between the admiral

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:45.990
and the aide-de-camp tell us
much about the relationship

00:47:45.990 --> 00:47:48.540
between Hood and de
Bude and Hood's service

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:51.670
on the oceanic front lines
of the American rebellion,

00:47:51.670 --> 00:47:53.730
yet they raised exciting
new questions

00:47:53.730 --> 00:47:56.980
about George III's
American Revolution.

00:47:56.980 --> 00:48:00.080
And now through the Georgian
Papers project and generosity

00:48:00.080 --> 00:48:03.320
of many, many people here and
not, we are getting access

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:05.180
to the-- that archive
that will help us

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:07.030
to answer those questions.

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:08.830
Thank you very much.

