00:50:34.100 --> 00:50:38.790
of the college while they're
there even though one's spending

00:50:38.790 --> 00:50:41.830
most of your time at Windsor.

00:50:41.830 --> 00:50:46.490
Now my objective now is going
to be to show you the importance

00:50:46.490 --> 00:50:48.990
of this archive for
American history

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:52.470
and specifically the
American Revolution.

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:55.860
And this is why I applaud
the Library of Congress

00:50:55.860 --> 00:50:59.490
and the Kluge Center
for its involvement

00:50:59.490 --> 00:51:04.110
and because this is important
albeit for the British side

00:51:04.110 --> 00:51:05.950
of the American Revolution.

00:51:05.950 --> 00:51:09.550
But the British side
is very essential part

00:51:09.550 --> 00:51:14.800
of understanding the American
Revolution more generally.

00:51:16.410 --> 00:51:21.900
George III was in some ways
the last king of England

00:51:21.900 --> 00:51:25.400
to rule in any real sense.

00:51:25.400 --> 00:51:29.870
It might be said by pedants
that there are important moments

00:51:29.870 --> 00:51:34.220
where monarchs did
intervene like William IV

00:51:34.220 --> 00:51:40.860
with the reformat-- and even
most recently the Queen in 1963,

00:51:40.860 --> 00:51:44.170
she appointed a prime
minister, Sir Alec Douglas-Home

00:51:44.170 --> 00:51:49.750
who was virtually unknown
at the time in a situation

00:51:49.750 --> 00:51:53.000
of the gridlock in parliament.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:56.500
But George III letters
has always been debated

00:51:56.500 --> 00:51:58.600
as to whether it
was a constitutional

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:00.990
or unconstitutional monarch.

00:52:00.990 --> 00:52:05.160
George III did have real power.

00:52:05.160 --> 00:52:11.280
And he was able to choose
members of the cabinet

00:52:11.280 --> 00:52:16.050
and he was able to choose
the prime minister as long

00:52:16.050 --> 00:52:18.480
as he chose a prime minister

00:52:18.480 --> 00:52:21.360
who generally had
support in parliament.

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:24.860
But that gave him
a lot of leeway.

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:30.360
George III was not responsible
for the policies that led

00:52:30.360 --> 00:52:34.910
to the American Revolution
even though he's blamed as such

00:52:34.910 --> 00:52:37.300
by the declaration
of independence.

00:52:37.300 --> 00:52:42.350
And John Adams in retirement
complained to Thomas Jefferson

00:52:42.350 --> 00:52:46.680
that he shouldn't have
called George III a tyrant.

00:52:46.680 --> 00:52:50.820
But George III does become
the leading war hawk.

00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:55.190
And this is one of the reasons
that these are the key papers,

00:52:55.190 --> 00:53:00.290
the papers of George
III for high politics

00:53:00.290 --> 00:53:04.070
and the military during
the American Revolution

00:53:04.070 --> 00:53:07.120
from the British side.

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:08.510
Unfortunately, the papers

00:53:08.510 --> 00:53:12.680
of Lord North are very
disappointing and very limited.

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:17.680
The only papers that really
compete would be those

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:21.910
of the colonial office
in the national archives.

00:53:21.910 --> 00:53:26.990
George III essentially
became obsessed with this--

00:53:26.990 --> 00:53:30.880
with the issue of America
after the Boston Tea Party.

00:53:30.880 --> 00:53:37.020
That was the moment that he
decided that war was inevitable

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:41.310
and he became, in the words
even of his own admirers,

00:53:41.310 --> 00:53:43.860
almost his own prime minister.

00:53:43.860 --> 00:53:49.670
He dominated Lord North who was
constantly trying to resign,

00:53:49.670 --> 00:53:54.420
who lost faith in the
conflict very early on.

00:53:54.420 --> 00:53:57.870
He refused to negotiate
with opposition leaders

00:53:57.870 --> 00:54:04.410
who were committed to withdraw
from America as early as 1778.

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:08.250
And he was almost
Churchillian in the words

00:54:08.250 --> 00:54:11.300
of Herbert Butterfield
who was a historian

00:54:11.300 --> 00:54:13.680
at Cambridge during
the Second World War

00:54:13.680 --> 00:54:16.620
and wrote this shortly
afterwards that he reminded

00:54:16.620 --> 00:54:19.170
of Churchill when
he read phrases like

00:54:19.170 --> 00:54:23.890
"If any 10 men will stand
beside me, I intend to go on."

00:54:23.890 --> 00:54:27.680
George III was so obsessed

00:54:27.680 --> 00:54:32.940
that he actually threatened
his abdication during the war

00:54:32.940 --> 00:54:37.720
before-- long before he wrote
the actual abdication letter.

00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:42.920
And when he heard about the
news of Yorktown, he sent--

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:46.980
well, up today, we would
think of almost like an email

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:49.500
because George III,
whenever he was writing,

00:54:49.500 --> 00:54:53.920
would put the exact
time of the day almost

00:54:53.920 --> 00:54:57.980
to the last second on the note.

00:54:57.980 --> 00:55:02.190
But in this particular message,
which was sent to the secretary

00:55:02.190 --> 00:55:08.280
of state for America in his
house in Pall Mall in London,

00:55:08.280 --> 00:55:10.410
he failed even to put
the date which shows

00:55:10.410 --> 00:55:11.940
that there was a certain anxiety

00:55:11.940 --> 00:55:14.530
because he just heard
about Yorktown.

00:55:14.530 --> 00:55:18.770
And he wrote to Germain who
was dining with nine guests.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:23.820
And the nine guests were unaware
in fact to the news of Yorktown

00:55:23.820 --> 00:55:28.360
but they knew something major is
happening when the message came

00:55:28.360 --> 00:55:31.830
from the king late at night
during a dinner party.

00:55:31.830 --> 00:55:35.630
And one of the guests happened
to say that they'd heard

00:55:35.630 --> 00:55:40.840
that the French foreign
minister died and how sad

00:55:40.840 --> 00:55:43.830
because the minister would
never know what the outcome

00:55:43.830 --> 00:55:46.940
of the American Revolution was.

00:55:46.940 --> 00:55:52.190
And Germain-- Lord Germain
said he did know the outcome

00:55:52.190 --> 00:55:55.460
of the American Revolution.

00:55:55.460 --> 00:55:58.130
And most of the party
at that point felt

00:55:58.130 --> 00:56:01.730
that they were referring to the
Battle of the Chesapeake Capes,

00:56:01.730 --> 00:56:05.080
because most people
still expected Cornwallis

00:56:05.080 --> 00:56:06.650
to be victorious.

00:56:06.650 --> 00:56:09.900
They're even calling
him an English Hannibal

00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:13.550
in the British newspapers.

00:56:13.550 --> 00:56:16.340
And then Germain passed
around the message

00:56:16.340 --> 00:56:18.950
which said he'd heard that
Cornwallis had surrendered

00:56:18.950 --> 00:56:22.680
at Yorktown but we
intend to go on.

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:28.000
This is a minor setback
like Saratoga but most

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:31.750
of the army is still
in place in New York.

00:56:31.750 --> 00:56:36.200
We still have cities throughout
the eastern seaboard including

00:56:36.200 --> 00:56:38.840
Savannah or in Charleston.

00:56:38.840 --> 00:56:43.620
We still got Canada
and we will fight on.

00:56:43.620 --> 00:56:46.320
And indeed, one of the reasons

00:56:46.320 --> 00:56:50.170
that North eventually
resigned was

00:56:50.170 --> 00:56:54.410
because he couldn't really
persuade the king for him

00:56:54.410 --> 00:56:57.820
to be able to give an
unequivocal commitment

00:56:57.820 --> 00:57:00.500
that Britain would
withdraw from America.

00:57:00.500 --> 00:57:05.940
And opposition leaders
came in to replace him.

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:11.650
George III during the American
Revolution made his main palace

00:57:11.650 --> 00:57:15.900
outside of London Windsor
Castle, where the archives are.

00:57:15.900 --> 00:57:20.050
And that is the round tower
where they're contained.

00:57:20.050 --> 00:57:23.280
I've always started
symbolically quite significant

00:57:23.280 --> 00:57:28.850
that he would base himself
in a castle during the war

00:57:28.850 --> 00:57:35.040
because both-- his father died
of course before becoming king

00:57:35.040 --> 00:57:37.260
but his grandfather George II

00:57:37.260 --> 00:57:39.030
and his great grandfather
George I,

00:57:39.030 --> 00:57:42.060
both of them [inaudible]
Windsor Castle.

00:57:42.060 --> 00:57:47.000
In fact, a lot of work had to
be done to make it inhabitable.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:51.660
George III would have military
music played constantly there.

00:57:51.660 --> 00:57:53.090
He even designed the kind

00:57:53.090 --> 00:57:57.870
of uniform coat wear
called the Windsor uniform

00:57:57.870 --> 00:58:03.340
that was introduced
towards the end of the war.

00:58:03.340 --> 00:58:07.090
And he obsessed about
every detail of the war.

00:58:07.090 --> 00:58:10.830
And that is very apparent
when you start to go

00:58:10.830 --> 00:58:13.610
through the correspondence.

00:58:13.610 --> 00:58:16.260
Now, Arthur alluded
earlier to the fact

00:58:16.260 --> 00:58:19.560
that correspondence was
published in the '20s

00:58:19.560 --> 00:58:22.100
by a man called Sir
John Fortescue,

00:58:22.100 --> 00:58:25.290
who's a remarkable librarian
of the royal archives

00:58:25.290 --> 00:58:27.440
and a remarkable historian

00:58:27.440 --> 00:58:32.710
who wrote multi-volume
histories of the British army.

00:58:32.710 --> 00:58:36.110
And although in terms
of their interpretation

00:58:36.110 --> 00:58:39.260
of attitudes, they're
very dated.

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:41.010
Nevertheless, John Shy,

00:58:41.010 --> 00:58:44.080
one of the America's
leading military historians

00:58:44.080 --> 00:58:45.560
of the American Revolution,

00:58:45.560 --> 00:58:49.860
he recently reprinted
the section dealing

00:58:49.860 --> 00:58:51.220
with the American Revolution

00:58:51.220 --> 00:58:56.330
because he particularly admired
the way Fortescue is very easily

00:58:56.330 --> 00:59:02.320
and briefly able to
summarize battles and events.

00:59:02.320 --> 00:59:05.510
But the problem with that
correspondence is firstly it's

00:59:05.510 --> 00:59:08.910
incomplete as we
again see in a moment.

00:59:08.910 --> 00:59:13.120
Secondly, his author alluded
it's not really reliable.

00:59:13.120 --> 00:59:16.210
And it was Sir Lewis
Namier who's regarded as one

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:19.730
of Britain's leading
20th century historians,

00:59:19.730 --> 00:59:24.230
who went through just the first
year and produce the volume

00:59:24.230 --> 00:59:29.150
of corrections and amendments
to Fortescue's series.

00:59:29.150 --> 00:59:33.800
Incidentally, that
had a credible effect

00:59:33.800 --> 00:59:36.920
to all documentary
editors afterwards.

00:59:36.920 --> 00:59:42.110
It sent shivers people
spying that because a lot

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:47.140
of these changes were
hardly significant,

00:59:47.140 --> 00:59:52.970
nevertheless it was a warning
never to entirely rely on this--

00:59:52.970 --> 00:59:56.830
on the printed edition.

00:59:56.830 --> 01:00:03.410
Thirdly, actually seeing the
original documents is in itself,

01:00:03.410 --> 01:00:08.460
does influence your
reading of them.

01:00:08.460 --> 01:00:15.000
This on the screen is a list
of George III's own hand

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:17.410
of ships of the French Navy.

01:00:17.410 --> 01:00:19.670
And one of the most
remarkable things to me--

01:00:19.670 --> 01:00:24.320
and I was actually curious
about George III's influence

01:00:24.320 --> 01:00:29.370
on strategy because like the
president of United States,

01:00:29.370 --> 01:00:32.840
he was commander-in-chief
of the army.

01:00:32.840 --> 01:00:37.800
But he actually knew by
name most of his officers.

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:43.950
He was also the most proficient
monarch in naval affairs

01:00:43.950 --> 01:00:48.880
since at least William
III, if not the equal

01:00:48.880 --> 01:00:50.300
of someone like James II.

01:00:50.300 --> 01:00:54.810
Supposedly, he knew off by
heart the soundings and depths

01:00:54.810 --> 01:00:59.850
of various harbors
around Europe.

01:00:59.850 --> 01:01:07.220
And I found lots of
letters and lists

01:01:07.220 --> 01:01:10.300
where he'd copied
in his own hand.

01:01:10.300 --> 01:01:16.430
The most remarkable is in fact
the Siege of Boston in 1775

01:01:16.430 --> 01:01:19.690
where he's got information
about ordnance.

01:01:19.690 --> 01:01:25.070
And what he do is he'd receive
the official papers from one

01:01:25.070 --> 01:01:28.050
of the secretaries of
state usually germane

01:01:28.050 --> 01:01:30.450
and then he copy it out.

01:01:30.450 --> 01:01:34.480
So, what was the
discovery for me was

01:01:34.480 --> 01:01:37.210
that of course he
had no secretary.

01:01:37.210 --> 01:01:41.390
This material was
thought of as so private.

01:01:41.390 --> 01:01:43.620
And he remained without
a secretary

01:01:43.620 --> 01:01:48.610
until really quite later on
when ill-health forced him

01:01:48.610 --> 01:01:50.240
to have a secretary.

01:01:50.240 --> 01:01:55.010
And so, all of this
material is in his own hand.

01:01:55.010 --> 01:02:01.810
Thanks to his keeping letters
and papers that we have so much

01:02:01.810 --> 01:02:06.590
of Lord North's correspondence
because North didn't keep

01:02:06.590 --> 01:02:09.030
as much for his own part.

01:02:09.030 --> 01:02:12.470
I mentioned that a lot of
papers that are admitted

01:02:12.470 --> 01:02:18.000
by Sir John Fortescue, the most
entertaining are the series

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:22.700
of the letters from a spy, and
it might have actually been more

01:02:22.700 --> 01:02:28.610
than one person, who
signs himself Aristarchus.

01:02:28.610 --> 01:02:34.860
I was asked by the BBC, was he
a kind of James Bond figure?

01:02:34.860 --> 01:02:37.810
And I said, I didn't think so
because he describes himself

01:02:37.810 --> 01:02:42.580
as being in his late 60s.

01:02:42.580 --> 01:02:47.490
Although he said he felt like a
younger man, sort of 40 years,

01:02:47.490 --> 01:02:51.240
his junior, but he was very
much stationary in London

01:02:51.240 --> 01:02:55.680
but receiving intelligence
reports especially from France.

01:02:55.680 --> 01:02:58.790
One of them describes a plot

01:02:58.790 --> 01:03:01.940
that they thought was
an assassination plot.

01:03:01.940 --> 01:03:05.940
They said the French know that
you often are seen walking alone

01:03:05.940 --> 01:03:10.380
in your garden without
anyone around you,

01:03:10.380 --> 01:03:13.250
and so that this was a warning.

01:03:13.250 --> 01:03:15.180
Another more entertaining
one was

01:03:15.180 --> 01:03:19.680
that a British agent had
been put up a chimney

01:03:19.680 --> 01:03:22.130
in which Benjamin Franklin--

01:03:22.130 --> 01:03:25.140
a room in which Benjamin
Franklin was meeting

01:03:25.140 --> 01:03:30.950
with the emperor of Austria
to overhear the conversation.

01:03:30.950 --> 01:03:33.830
But some of it goes beyond.

01:03:33.830 --> 01:03:35.820
And I always imagine
that Fortescue

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:37.910
as a military historian
is mystic

01:03:37.910 --> 01:03:40.150
because he didn't think the
intelligence is very good.

01:03:40.150 --> 01:03:41.900
That was always been my guess.

01:03:41.900 --> 01:03:46.770
So, I really don't understand
why would particular letters--

01:03:46.770 --> 01:03:52.380
there are even letters of Lord
North that are not printed

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:53.680
in the correspondence.

01:03:53.680 --> 01:03:56.830
I'm not sure if it
was just negligence

01:03:56.830 --> 01:03:59.120
or if he had a specific reason.

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:02.200
But there are other
intelligence reports

01:04:02.200 --> 01:04:03.910
that really are very important.

01:04:03.910 --> 01:04:07.880
I thought one of the most
important came in a booklet

01:04:07.880 --> 01:04:13.660
and it's from 1777,
1781 and it's a book

01:04:13.660 --> 01:04:20.020
of naval intelligence by British
spies based near the coast near

01:04:20.020 --> 01:04:24.300
the port of Brest watching the
movements of the French fleet.

01:04:24.300 --> 01:04:27.560
And that is pretty critical
because one of the reasons

01:04:27.560 --> 01:04:31.460
that British got it wrong
in Yorktown is that one

01:04:31.460 --> 01:04:35.250
of the only times in the war
they had bad naval intelligence.

01:04:35.250 --> 01:04:37.370
The British planned to have a--

01:04:37.370 --> 01:04:39.370
what was known as
a [inaudible] navy.

01:04:39.370 --> 01:04:43.060
And that would be navy that was
strong enough to defeat France

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:45.640
and Spain simultaneously.

01:04:45.640 --> 01:04:48.640
Nearly for all of
the 18th century,

01:04:48.640 --> 01:04:51.280
the British had naval
superiority.

01:04:51.280 --> 01:04:53.110
It was the basis
of their empire,

01:04:53.110 --> 01:04:56.550
their control of the seas.

01:04:56.550 --> 01:04:59.200
But the battle of the
Chesapeake Capes is one

01:04:59.200 --> 01:05:02.600
of the only battles
they really lost.

01:05:02.600 --> 01:05:05.360
And it was a loss
even though much

01:05:05.360 --> 01:05:07.640
of it was simply drifting apart.

01:05:07.640 --> 01:05:10.730
But the fact that the
British were not able

01:05:10.730 --> 01:05:12.910
to defeat the French
Navy and open

01:05:12.910 --> 01:05:17.290
up the Chesapeake
represented a major defeat.

01:05:17.290 --> 01:05:22.000
And one of the reasons
was bad intelligence.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.460
And he's very curious
because the two commanders,

01:05:24.460 --> 01:05:27.780
army commanders would blame
each other after the war.

01:05:27.780 --> 01:05:30.730
Sir Henry Clinton, the
commander-in-chief in New York,

01:05:30.730 --> 01:05:37.180
Lord Cornwallis in Yorktown,
they would blame each other and

01:05:37.180 --> 01:05:41.090
yet both have been misled
and both had preceded

01:05:41.090 --> 01:05:44.930
on the assumption that Britain
would've had the superior navy.

01:05:44.930 --> 01:05:47.580
Had they done so, it
would've been possible

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:52.460
to simply ferry Cornwallis out
Yorktown and to get him back

01:05:52.460 --> 01:05:58.070
to New York or to Charleston.

01:05:58.070 --> 01:06:00.620
Other papers that are
important and they're more

01:06:00.620 --> 01:06:02.330
than just papers of George III,

01:06:02.330 --> 01:06:08.210
Jim spoke about Sir
Samuel Hood's papers

01:06:08.210 --> 01:06:10.910
and those papers are
very interesting too

01:06:10.910 --> 01:06:13.940
for the royal family
because Sir Samuel Hood

01:06:13.940 --> 01:06:17.150
for a long while looked
after Prince William.

01:06:17.150 --> 01:06:20.430
It was part of George III's
obsession with this war

01:06:20.430 --> 01:06:24.220
that he sent two of his
own sons into the military,

01:06:24.220 --> 01:06:27.500
one into the army and the
14-year-old Prince William

01:06:27.500 --> 01:06:31.870
into the navy where he
essentially was eye witness

01:06:31.870 --> 01:06:35.660
to some horrendous
moments almost

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:38.030
from the moment that
he left England.

01:06:38.030 --> 01:06:43.080
The father was incredibly
disappointed with him later

01:06:43.080 --> 01:06:48.370
on because he acquired
such foul language, manners

01:06:48.370 --> 01:06:52.340
and alcohol habits from
his time in the navy.

01:06:52.340 --> 01:06:55.720
But Hood oversaw him and
gives us a lot of information.

01:06:55.720 --> 01:06:57.670
Hood was also in the Caribbean.

01:06:57.670 --> 01:07:00.040
So, it's a very important source

01:07:00.040 --> 01:07:02.450
for naval warfare
in the Caribbean.

01:07:02.450 --> 01:07:05.670
These materials were
never used by any

01:07:05.670 --> 01:07:07.890
of Sir Samuel Hood's
biographies.

01:07:07.890 --> 01:07:10.870
So they really were unknown

01:07:10.870 --> 01:07:16.110
and they do represent a
very major new discovery.

01:07:16.110 --> 01:07:18.620
A third set of papers that
are important are those

01:07:18.620 --> 01:07:22.500
of Prince William
himself who corresponded

01:07:22.500 --> 01:07:24.750
with his father throughout.

01:07:24.750 --> 01:07:28.400
He was the only member of
the British royal family

01:07:28.400 --> 01:07:33.120
to visit America before
it became independent.

01:07:33.120 --> 01:07:38.210
And what was most dramatic
to me was his descriptions

01:07:38.210 --> 01:07:40.390
of British occupied New York.

01:07:40.390 --> 01:07:46.180
And what was amusing was
his description of arriving

01:07:46.180 --> 01:07:51.130
and he was greeted by Henry
Clinton who's commander-in-chief

01:07:51.130 --> 01:07:55.200
who you think might had other
preoccupations at the time

01:07:55.200 --> 01:07:57.980
because this was literally
about a month before Yorktown

01:07:57.980 --> 01:08:03.660
where people are going mad
in New York with the fleet

01:08:03.660 --> 01:08:06.200
of Sir Samuel Hood
having returned,

01:08:06.200 --> 01:08:08.650
knocked about by de Grasse.

01:08:08.650 --> 01:08:11.780
And supposedly they were trying
to refit it and repair it to go

01:08:11.780 --> 01:08:17.700
and have another attempt
to release Cornwallis.

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:23.930
But when Prince William arrived,
he met Sir Henry Clinton

01:08:23.930 --> 01:08:26.810
and he walked through what
he called the Parade Ground

01:08:26.810 --> 01:08:29.070
but what we call Bowling Green.

01:08:29.070 --> 01:08:32.470
And at this moment,
his relationship

01:08:32.470 --> 01:08:36.180
with his father was
incredibly tense

01:08:36.180 --> 01:08:39.970
because the father really
was upset by now at the sort

01:08:39.970 --> 01:08:42.790
of relationships the
son was developing,

01:08:42.790 --> 01:08:45.120
the fact that he
wasn't studying.

01:08:45.120 --> 01:08:49.590
And he said as he walked
through Bowling Green,

01:08:49.590 --> 01:08:52.210
and I saw the pedestal

01:08:52.210 --> 01:08:55.380
where once he imagined the
statue stood [laughter].

01:08:55.380 --> 01:08:59.280
And it's difficult not to think

01:08:59.280 --> 01:09:05.930
that this was a [inaudible]
dad [laughter].

01:09:05.930 --> 01:09:07.840
Also, part of the papers,

01:09:07.840 --> 01:09:13.830
although they are being
digitally copied separately,

01:09:13.830 --> 01:09:17.180
but an important part of
the papers are the maps

01:09:17.180 --> 01:09:21.110
and military plans
and engravings

01:09:21.110 --> 01:09:23.310
in the royal collection.

01:09:23.310 --> 01:09:26.170
These are very remarkable.

01:09:26.170 --> 01:09:29.940
I looked at several,
the Bunker Hill,

01:09:29.940 --> 01:09:32.200
and I initially thought
I recognize these.

01:09:32.200 --> 01:09:39.040
These are the famous plans of
Bunker Hill that you'll see them

01:09:39.040 --> 01:09:40.620
in almost every textbook.

01:09:40.620 --> 01:09:45.900
And then I realized they showed
different parts of the day

01:09:45.900 --> 01:09:49.680
of Bunker Hill that these
had not been reproduced.

01:09:49.680 --> 01:09:52.070
Now, I can tell you
that the Library

01:09:52.070 --> 01:09:56.390
of Congress actually
did microfilm

01:09:56.390 --> 01:09:58.820
of these many years ago,

01:09:58.820 --> 01:10:02.040
but I don't think many people
would be aware of that.

01:10:02.040 --> 01:10:06.350
But the Library of Congress is
the most important secondary

01:10:06.350 --> 01:10:09.180
repository for a lot
of British materials.

01:10:09.180 --> 01:10:13.560
They copied all of the
colonial office materials many

01:10:13.560 --> 01:10:14.860
decades ago.

01:10:14.860 --> 01:10:16.820
So it's an excellent
place to come

01:10:16.820 --> 01:10:20.310
and study the American
Revolution.

01:10:20.310 --> 01:10:21.900
Nevertheless, when
you're dealing with maps

01:10:21.900 --> 01:10:23.410
and engravings, you
really do want

01:10:23.410 --> 01:10:29.190
to see the original not
look at it on microfilm.

01:10:29.190 --> 01:10:34.510
And finally people
mentioned that there are lots

01:10:34.510 --> 01:10:41.830
of miscellaneous papers at least
to do with trying to get his--

01:10:41.830 --> 01:10:45.320
buy out his son from letters

01:10:45.320 --> 01:10:47.750
that the son had
foolishly written--

01:10:47.750 --> 01:10:49.660
this was the future George IV--

01:10:49.660 --> 01:10:55.360
to his mistress and the father
had to pay a lot of money

01:10:55.360 --> 01:10:57.670
to get these letters back.

01:10:57.670 --> 01:11:05.290
The woman involved was a very
smart actress and she managed

01:11:05.290 --> 01:11:08.050
to secure a very
large sum of money.

01:11:08.050 --> 01:11:12.580
She then went on to be the
partner [inaudible] probably the

01:11:12.580 --> 01:11:15.680
most hated British
officer in America

01:11:15.680 --> 01:11:19.210
but it's often said although
people regard [inaudible]

01:11:19.210 --> 01:11:22.170
memoirs as a lot of
lies, but they're some

01:11:22.170 --> 01:11:25.250
of the best written memoirs
by any British soldier.

01:11:25.250 --> 01:11:28.350
But that's because she was
a novelist and a writer

01:11:28.350 --> 01:11:32.070
and it almost certainly a
ghost written his memoir.

01:11:32.070 --> 01:11:36.650
All I can say by ending and any
of you might consider applying

01:11:36.650 --> 01:11:39.040
for this fellowship, is

01:11:39.040 --> 01:11:42.250
that it's just the most
wonderful location.

01:11:42.250 --> 01:11:46.990
These are a few photos that
I just took with my iPhone.

01:11:46.990 --> 01:11:53.250
The Nell Gwynn coffee house
supposedly there are tunnels

01:11:53.250 --> 01:11:54.700
from that coffee house

01:11:54.700 --> 01:11:57.970
which Nell Gwynn used
to see Charles II.

01:11:57.970 --> 01:12:00.310
There's a changing
of the guard just

01:12:00.310 --> 01:12:03.670
like Buckingham Palace everyday.

01:12:03.670 --> 01:12:06.680
And of course it's terribly
tempting because I meant

01:12:06.680 --> 01:12:08.730
to be inside the castle.

01:12:08.730 --> 01:12:14.560
But there's always so much
going on outside and, you know,

01:12:14.560 --> 01:12:19.970
just observing sunset-- there's
an even song there everyday,

01:12:19.970 --> 01:12:23.400
a beautiful song, even
sung in St. George's Chapel

01:12:23.400 --> 01:12:27.100
where Elizabeth I
is also buried.

01:12:27.100 --> 01:12:31.130
And it's worth going to just
purely as a good concert

01:12:31.130 --> 01:12:33.430
and you can also
get free admission

01:12:33.430 --> 01:12:36.180
to the castle if you go to that.

01:12:36.180 --> 01:12:40.750
So I'll just leave you
with those visitors.

01:12:40.750 --> 01:12:44.280
But I'll end by saying I think
that is wonderful the Library

01:12:44.280 --> 01:12:45.580
of Congress is involved.

01:12:45.580 --> 01:12:50.810
I've met with Carla Hayden
at Monticello and again

01:12:50.810 --> 01:12:52.110
