01:17:18.520 --> 01:17:21.650
with you [laughter].

01:17:21.650 --> 01:17:23.930
What compels us still
as we explore

01:17:23.930 --> 01:17:27.150
and shape this project going
forward is really the potential

01:17:27.150 --> 01:17:28.980
of the project.

01:17:28.980 --> 01:17:31.180
Refresh historical understanding

01:17:31.180 --> 01:17:35.130
that is really what makes
this project so exciting.

01:17:35.130 --> 01:17:38.190
I don't think there's anyone
here that I have to persuade

01:17:38.190 --> 01:17:40.000
about the importance of history.

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:42.640
I'm going to just go
with assuming that.

01:17:42.640 --> 01:17:45.770
But history is the context
in which we make decision,

01:17:45.770 --> 01:17:50.380
everyday consequential and
minute, domestic and national.

01:17:50.380 --> 01:17:53.450
And these archives give
us an opportunity to think

01:17:53.450 --> 01:17:57.400
with fresh evidence about the
history that shapes the world

01:17:57.400 --> 01:17:59.740
that we live in right now.

01:17:59.740 --> 01:18:03.280
In part it's the fresh material
like the Aristarchus material

01:18:03.280 --> 01:18:05.770
that Andrew just discussed,
the de Bude correspondence

01:18:05.770 --> 01:18:08.260
that Jim's analyzed, but
it's also a chance to think

01:18:08.260 --> 01:18:10.860
about how we can see
things in a fresh light,

01:18:10.860 --> 01:18:13.980
make new connections or
create an entirely new frame

01:18:13.980 --> 01:18:16.160
of reference or subjective
analysis.

01:18:16.160 --> 01:18:19.100
We can use it to see people
and subjects that may have been

01:18:19.100 --> 01:18:22.040
or may have seemed to be
marginal to its interest

01:18:22.040 --> 01:18:23.490
that is the interest
of the court

01:18:23.490 --> 01:18:25.750
but in fact incredibly
important,

01:18:25.750 --> 01:18:28.520
especially in an American
and Atlantic context.

01:18:28.520 --> 01:18:31.010
And the Omohundro
Institute's chief investment

01:18:31.010 --> 01:18:33.540
in this project is
entirely along these lines.

01:18:33.540 --> 01:18:36.540
To take the opportunity of this
incredible archive that bear

01:18:36.540 --> 01:18:39.190
so importantly on our
country's early history,

01:18:39.190 --> 01:18:41.390
to illuminate fresh
histories of early America

01:18:41.390 --> 01:18:42.690
and the Atlantic world.

01:18:42.690 --> 01:18:45.780
Just one of these potential
topics is the nature

01:18:45.780 --> 01:18:49.790
of 18th century women's
intellectual exchange.

01:18:49.790 --> 01:18:53.800
In the 18th century, a
robust intellectual exchange

01:18:53.800 --> 01:18:56.830
across the Atlantic,
sometimes called the Republic

01:18:56.830 --> 01:18:59.890
of Letters included
philosophers, scientists,

01:18:59.890 --> 01:19:03.420
and statesmen from England and
the continent, and Americans

01:19:03.420 --> 01:19:06.320
such as most famously
probably Benjamin Franklin

01:19:06.320 --> 01:19:07.620
and Thomas Jefferson.

01:19:07.620 --> 01:19:09.330
Now this developing web

01:19:09.330 --> 01:19:12.420
of intellectual connection
was fueled by an exchange

01:19:12.420 --> 01:19:15.120
of writing, mostly letters
and other manuscript material

01:19:15.120 --> 01:19:18.250
but also printed books,
treatises, pamphlets.

01:19:18.250 --> 01:19:22.100
Jefferson and Franklin produced
and received roughly 10,000

01:19:22.100 --> 01:19:24.940
and 15,000 letters respectively

01:19:24.940 --> 01:19:27.820
in their lifetimes giving
you some idea of the volume

01:19:27.820 --> 01:19:30.480
of this Republic of Letters
and anybody who's tried

01:19:30.480 --> 01:19:34.330
to get their email inbox down
to zero can appreciate the size

01:19:34.330 --> 01:19:36.280
of this endeavor.

01:19:36.280 --> 01:19:39.020
Scholars have mapped
the Republic of Letters

01:19:39.020 --> 01:19:41.220
in putting data on
authors and recipients

01:19:41.220 --> 01:19:42.760
to produce data visualization.

01:19:42.760 --> 01:19:44.080
There's actually
terrific project

01:19:44.080 --> 01:19:46.290
out at Stanford University
called Mapping the Republic

01:19:46.290 --> 01:19:47.590
of Letters.

01:19:47.590 --> 01:19:49.970
For America, the primary
observation of mapping

01:19:49.970 --> 01:19:52.010
that republic is
that the Republic

01:19:52.010 --> 01:19:55.980
of Letters looks very focused
on England and particularly

01:19:55.980 --> 01:19:58.120
on London networks that
is for the Americans

01:19:58.120 --> 01:19:59.420
who are participating.

01:19:59.420 --> 01:20:01.560
And of course the most
elaborate work has been done

01:20:01.560 --> 01:20:03.040
on the primarily male
participants in these networks.

01:20:03.040 --> 01:20:06.060
But women's literally

01:20:06.060 --> 01:20:08.500
and intellectual networks
were also flourishing

01:20:08.500 --> 01:20:09.800
in the 18th century.

01:20:09.800 --> 01:20:12.550
And they may not yield to
the kinds of data points

01:20:12.550 --> 01:20:15.780
and mapping approach but the
voluminous correspondents of men

01:20:15.780 --> 01:20:17.850
like Jefferson and
Franklin might,

01:20:17.850 --> 01:20:20.830
but rather take some teasing
out of themes and influences.

01:20:20.830 --> 01:20:24.210
Now scholars have studied
closely what's known

01:20:24.210 --> 01:20:27.400
as the bluestocking circle
of women writers in England.

01:20:27.400 --> 01:20:30.010
And other scholars have also
studied early American groups

01:20:30.010 --> 01:20:32.820
of women, particularly in
the urban hubs of Boston,

01:20:32.820 --> 01:20:35.240
Philadelphia, and New
York who are writing

01:20:35.240 --> 01:20:36.950
and reading one another's work.

01:20:36.950 --> 01:20:38.680
How might these groups
have intersected

01:20:38.680 --> 01:20:40.810
and what can the
Georgian Papers illuminate

01:20:40.810 --> 01:20:44.500
in fresh possibilities
about these women writers?

01:20:44.500 --> 01:20:47.510
So, I want to invite to take
three quick steps with me

01:20:47.510 --> 01:20:49.600
through women's transatlantic
connection centering

01:20:49.600 --> 01:20:52.640
on intellectual and
literally concerns.

01:20:52.640 --> 01:20:57.940
The first concerns, two of the
most prominent women of England

01:20:57.940 --> 01:21:00.420
and America, respectively,
Catharine Macaulay

01:21:00.420 --> 01:21:02.340
and Mercy Otis Warren,

01:21:02.340 --> 01:21:06.040
whose connection offers us
just a quick place to begin.

01:21:06.040 --> 01:21:09.190
Macaulay was one of the most
prominent public women in an era

01:21:09.190 --> 01:21:11.890
in which very few women were
either and certainly not

01:21:11.890 --> 01:21:13.640
as intellectual as we've
heard already a lot

01:21:13.640 --> 01:21:16.320
about princesses and mistresses.

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:20.280
She was known colloquially
as the female historian.

01:21:20.280 --> 01:21:23.380
Macaulay wrote a history
of 17th century England,

01:21:23.380 --> 01:21:26.030
the history of England from
the ascension of James I

01:21:26.030 --> 01:21:28.670
to the revolution
in eighth volumes

01:21:28.670 --> 01:21:31.200
with the first volume
published in 1763

01:21:31.200 --> 01:21:34.660
and the last 20 years
later in 1783.

01:21:34.660 --> 01:21:37.760
This was a political history
that is a history of politics

01:21:37.760 --> 01:21:41.670
and governance but also a quite
politically charged history.

01:21:41.670 --> 01:21:45.670
It [inaudible] for mostly Whigs
and was seen as a kind small

01:21:45.670 --> 01:21:48.330
"r" republican work
and anti-royalist,

01:21:48.330 --> 01:21:50.560
though not necessary
straightforwardly so.

01:21:50.560 --> 01:21:53.180
She was incredibly
critical of Oliver Cromwell.

01:21:53.180 --> 01:21:56.950
For example, she called
him a glorious usurper.

01:21:56.950 --> 01:21:58.790
She's a great writer.

01:21:58.790 --> 01:22:00.570
I hear applause out there

01:22:00.570 --> 01:22:02.460
for being glorious
usurper, OK [laughs].

01:22:02.460 --> 01:22:08.080
Macaulay's history was praised
by major figures of the day

01:22:08.080 --> 01:22:10.170
in England even by
William Pitt for examples

01:22:10.170 --> 01:22:12.210
in the House of Commons.

01:22:12.210 --> 01:22:14.160
Mercy Otis Warren's
life was marked

01:22:14.160 --> 01:22:16.840
by the revolutionary
era in which she lived.

01:22:16.840 --> 01:22:19.890
Born of a mayflower family
mother and a lawyer father,

01:22:19.890 --> 01:22:22.120
mercy and her siblings
were raised and educated

01:22:22.120 --> 01:22:23.990
to an extraordinary
high standard.

01:22:23.990 --> 01:22:27.180
One of her brothers, James Otis,
for example, authored key text

01:22:27.180 --> 01:22:30.230
to the American Revolution such
as the famous pamphlet "Rights

01:22:30.230 --> 01:22:32.700
of the British Colonies
Asserted and Proved".

01:22:32.700 --> 01:22:35.480
He famously articulated the
principle of no taxation

01:22:35.480 --> 01:22:38.030
without representation
in regards to the scheme

01:22:38.030 --> 01:22:41.530
to collect taxes on American
consumption of British goods.

01:22:41.530 --> 01:22:44.420
Mercy wrote in a variety
of genres including one

01:22:44.420 --> 01:22:47.720
of the more significant
publications of the late 1780s,

01:22:47.720 --> 01:22:50.160
advocating for the
inclusion of a bill of rights

01:22:50.160 --> 01:22:52.270
in the new US constitution.

01:22:52.270 --> 01:22:56.570
And in 1805, she published the
product of decades of writing

01:22:56.570 --> 01:22:58.290
about the unfolding events

01:22:58.290 --> 01:23:01.050
of the revolution
and its aftermath.

01:23:01.050 --> 01:23:04.930
Thomas Jefferson wrote that her
rise, progress, and termination

01:23:04.930 --> 01:23:07.560
of the American Revolution,
was "a truthful

01:23:07.560 --> 01:23:10.250
and insightful account
of the last 30 years

01:23:10.250 --> 01:23:13.030
that will furnish a more
instructive lesson to mankind

01:23:13.030 --> 01:23:15.750
than any earlier
period in history."

01:23:15.750 --> 01:23:18.520
Because of Warren's
increasingly anti-federalist

01:23:18.520 --> 01:23:20.260
and Jeffersonian
leanings however,

01:23:20.260 --> 01:23:23.910
John Adams who had been a long
time dear friend denounced

01:23:23.910 --> 01:23:25.470
the work.

01:23:25.470 --> 01:23:28.460
These two extraordinary women,
these two historians, Macaulay

01:23:28.460 --> 01:23:31.700
and Warren, maintained a long
and intense correspondence

01:23:31.700 --> 01:23:34.020
across two crucial decades.

01:23:34.020 --> 01:23:38.360
They began to correspond in
1773 and Warren's last letter

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:42.950
to Macaulay was in May of 1791,
the year that Macaulay died.

01:23:42.950 --> 01:23:45.520
In an early exchange
about whether women could

01:23:45.520 --> 01:23:47.510
and should express
political opinions,

01:23:47.510 --> 01:23:50.420
obviously they were preaching
to one another there,

01:23:50.420 --> 01:23:54.720
Mercy Warren wrote to her famous
friend, "I disregard the opinion

01:23:54.720 --> 01:23:57.450
that women make but in
different politicians.

01:23:57.450 --> 01:24:00.520
When the observations are
just and do honor to the heart

01:24:00.520 --> 01:24:04.170
and character, I think it very
immaterial whether they flow

01:24:04.170 --> 01:24:06.950
from a female lip or are
thundered in the Senate

01:24:06.950 --> 01:24:10.130
in the bolder language
of the other sex."

01:24:10.130 --> 01:24:13.140
Macaulay and Warren's
friendship was tested as they

01:24:13.140 --> 01:24:16.050
like many other figures in this
period who are deeply involved

01:24:16.050 --> 01:24:18.780
and invested disagreed,
sometimes mildly

01:24:18.780 --> 01:24:21.000
and sometimes sharply,
sometimes privately

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:23.100
and sometimes actually
quite publicly.

01:24:23.100 --> 01:24:26.220
But their mutual
admiration never waned.

01:24:26.220 --> 01:24:28.420
Macaulay visited
America for over a year,

01:24:28.420 --> 01:24:30.270
beginning in the summer of 1784.

01:24:30.270 --> 01:24:32.100
And she spent time
in Boston with Warren

01:24:32.100 --> 01:24:33.970
and she actually spent
time at Mount Vernon too,

01:24:33.970 --> 01:24:35.960
visiting George and
Martha Washington.

01:24:35.960 --> 01:24:39.940
Now that we've established
something of the extent

01:24:39.940 --> 01:24:42.560
of women's transatlantic
connections, courtesy of Warren

01:24:42.560 --> 01:24:45.040
and Macaulay, let us turn to one
that brings us into the courts

01:24:45.040 --> 01:24:47.280
and the Georgian Papers.

01:24:47.280 --> 01:24:48.600
This example concerns one

01:24:48.600 --> 01:24:50.970
of the 18th century's
most celebrated novelists,

01:24:50.970 --> 01:24:52.540
Frances Burney known as Fanny.

01:24:52.540 --> 01:24:56.330
Burney was a prodigious diarist.

01:24:56.330 --> 01:24:57.630
In fact just this year,

01:24:57.630 --> 01:25:01.100
the Guardian described
her edited diaries as one

01:25:01.100 --> 01:25:04.870
of the 100 most important
nonfiction works of all time.

01:25:04.870 --> 01:25:07.530
She's a great diarist
and great writer.

01:25:07.530 --> 01:25:11.550
She published her first novel in
1778 and her second, "Cecilia",

01:25:11.550 --> 01:25:14.050
to great acclaim in 1782.

01:25:14.050 --> 01:25:17.190
The enthusiastic reception for
"Cecilia" included attention

01:25:17.190 --> 01:25:18.710
from the royal family.

01:25:18.710 --> 01:25:20.810
The queen urged her
daughters to read it

01:25:20.810 --> 01:25:22.510
for amusement and for education.

01:25:22.510 --> 01:25:26.390
And in 1785, Queen
Charlotte asked Burney

01:25:26.390 --> 01:25:29.960
to accept the position at court,
which the novelist accepted.

01:25:29.960 --> 01:25:32.640
She was one of the queen's
ladies for five years,

01:25:32.640 --> 01:25:35.870
difficult ones that included
King George III's first intense

01:25:35.870 --> 01:25:38.310
period of mental illness.

01:25:38.310 --> 01:25:41.220
We've heard quite a bit about
the king's qualities as a sort

01:25:41.220 --> 01:25:43.900
of intellectual magpie you might
have gathered he was interested

01:25:43.900 --> 01:25:46.660
in all kinds of different
things from agriculture

01:25:46.660 --> 01:25:48.800
to astronomy to statecraft.

01:25:48.800 --> 01:25:52.840
And Charlotte too had a lively
curiosity for botany, for music,

01:25:52.840 --> 01:25:57.030
and language but especially
for history and literature.

01:25:57.030 --> 01:25:59.520
She was keen to have
bluestockings around her.

01:25:59.520 --> 01:26:01.100
Burney wasn't the only one.

01:26:01.100 --> 01:26:03.110
And they remained close.

01:26:03.110 --> 01:26:05.630
Burney remained close
to the princesses too

01:26:05.630 --> 01:26:08.930
after she left royal service.

01:26:08.930 --> 01:26:13.170
Burney's reputation flourished
internationally and in America.

01:26:13.170 --> 01:26:18.100
The London edition of "Cecilia"
was advertised as early as 1784

01:26:18.100 --> 01:26:22.530
in America and was printed in
an American edition in 1793.

01:26:22.530 --> 01:26:24.280
Now these novels are
sometimes described

01:26:24.280 --> 01:26:25.880
as precursor to Jane Austin.

01:26:25.880 --> 01:26:28.740
They're witty, they're
country house settings.

01:26:28.740 --> 01:26:31.260
In these books, the
women are always readers.

01:26:31.260 --> 01:26:34.570
And in fact Austin's-- the title

01:26:34.570 --> 01:26:37.210
of probably Austin's most
significant novel comes

01:26:37.210 --> 01:26:39.820
from a line in "Cecilia" where
a character notes that the whole

01:26:39.820 --> 01:26:42.500
of this unfortunate
business has been the result

01:26:42.500 --> 01:26:44.800
of pride and prejudice.

01:26:46.430 --> 01:26:48.660
Burney' reputation
among American educators

01:26:48.660 --> 01:26:50.190
in particular only grew.

01:26:50.190 --> 01:26:52.600
As the 19th century
dawned, there was a rush

01:26:52.600 --> 01:26:55.380
of new academies founded for the
education of privileged girls

01:26:55.380 --> 01:26:58.300
in America and an embrace
of the value of education

01:26:58.300 --> 01:27:00.470
for free girls of elite families

01:27:00.470 --> 01:27:03.050
as a benefit to the
new republic.

01:27:03.050 --> 01:27:06.090
Among the great writers and
advocates was another Bostonian,

01:27:06.090 --> 01:27:07.630
Judith Sargent Murray.

01:27:07.630 --> 01:27:10.480
She was an early advocate
for equality of the sexes,

01:27:10.480 --> 01:27:13.540
publishing an essay by that
name in 1790, well in advance

01:27:13.540 --> 01:27:15.320
of Mary Wollstonecraft in fact.

01:27:15.320 --> 01:27:19.020
And she gathered her many
essays together in 1798.

01:27:19.020 --> 01:27:20.990
Just as Americans were
beginning to think

01:27:20.990 --> 01:27:24.320
about creating a new national
literature and she published

01:27:24.320 --> 01:27:26.530
in three volumes "The Gleaner",

01:27:26.530 --> 01:27:28.400
which incorporated
her political views

01:27:28.400 --> 01:27:30.550
and especially her interest
in women's education.

01:27:30.550 --> 01:27:32.990
And she'd go on to
found a women's--

01:27:32.990 --> 01:27:35.920
a girl school herself
with two friends in 1802.

01:27:35.920 --> 01:27:40.500
And in "The Gleaner" which
Murray is publishing in 1798,

01:27:40.500 --> 01:27:41.870
she advocated for the value

01:27:41.870 --> 01:27:45.530
of Burney's novels,
especially "Cecilia".

01:27:45.530 --> 01:27:48.760
In a period when novels were
often dismissed as frivolous

01:27:48.760 --> 01:27:51.050
or not reflective of the
virtues of the new nation,

01:27:51.050 --> 01:27:54.480
there's actually a very snarky
John Quincy Adams quote about

01:27:54.480 --> 01:27:56.500
"Cecilia" specifically.

01:27:56.500 --> 01:27:59.850
But Murray and others made
clear that in their reflections

01:27:59.850 --> 01:28:01.630
on character and circumstances,

01:28:01.630 --> 01:28:04.830
novels could be essential
reading and learning.

01:28:04.830 --> 01:28:07.090
And here of course she's
echoing Queen Charlotte

01:28:07.090 --> 01:28:09.420
who if you remember
advocated Burney's books

01:28:09.420 --> 01:28:12.260
for her daughters
for the same reasons.

01:28:12.260 --> 01:28:14.440
And now let's bring
this quickly together.

01:28:14.440 --> 01:28:17.670
The transatlantic connections
among women intellectuals,

01:28:17.670 --> 01:28:20.470
they were reading one another's
work, writing about one another

01:28:20.470 --> 01:28:23.880
and even directly communicating,
in fact across political--

01:28:23.880 --> 01:28:26.460
what we might think of
as political device.

01:28:26.460 --> 01:28:28.810
My third example here
concerns the place of history

01:28:28.810 --> 01:28:31.560
in geography in women's
education in the late 18th

01:28:31.560 --> 01:28:33.200
and early 19th century.

01:28:33.200 --> 01:28:35.280
In those early female academies,

01:28:35.280 --> 01:28:37.860
like the one Judith
Sargent Murray helped found,

01:28:37.860 --> 01:28:40.770
the curriculum included novels
in place of course in poetry

01:28:40.770 --> 01:28:44.080
but it also emphasize
the importance of history

01:28:44.080 --> 01:28:46.730
and geography essential
to the education of women

01:28:46.730 --> 01:28:49.220
as Denisons [phonetic]
of this new nation.

01:28:49.220 --> 01:28:51.410
And here you'll see on
the right there an example

01:28:51.410 --> 01:28:54.680
from a Quaker school right
outside of Philadelphia

01:28:54.680 --> 01:28:57.230
where teachers created their
own textbooks of poetry

01:28:57.230 --> 01:29:00.020
and also had their students
create their own globes.

01:29:00.020 --> 01:29:03.180
This stitched globe is actually
it's got hardcore interior

01:29:03.180 --> 01:29:06.170
and batting around it and
there are number of examples

01:29:06.170 --> 01:29:07.470
from this particular school,

01:29:07.470 --> 01:29:10.270
the Westtown School,
as well as others.

01:29:10.270 --> 01:29:12.270
And then the longitude
is stitched.

01:29:12.270 --> 01:29:14.890
It's really faded there but
it's a really beautiful object.

01:29:14.890 --> 01:29:16.440
It's [inaudible]
center right now

01:29:16.440 --> 01:29:18.560
at the Boston Public Library.

01:29:18.560 --> 01:29:21.730
This stitched globe
helped these young women

01:29:21.730 --> 01:29:24.360
as they had male
students for centuries,

01:29:24.360 --> 01:29:26.770
not only with basic
geographical orientation

01:29:26.770 --> 01:29:28.700
but with geometry and astronomy.

01:29:28.700 --> 01:29:32.820
And back inside Windsor
Castle, Queen Charlotte,

01:29:32.820 --> 01:29:35.980
her six daughters, the
princesses and their governesses

01:29:35.980 --> 01:29:37.280
and ladies in waiting

01:29:37.280 --> 01:29:40.790
like Frances Burney were
creating curricula of their own.

01:29:40.790 --> 01:29:44.340
The Queen established at
Frogmore House a private retreat

01:29:44.340 --> 01:29:48.320
on the grounds at Windsor,
a printing press of her own.

01:29:48.320 --> 01:29:50.520
And there, among
many others projects,

01:29:50.520 --> 01:29:52.980
they created boxed
sets of historical

01:29:52.980 --> 01:29:55.070
and geographical information.

01:29:55.070 --> 01:29:58.390
Here you see, on
the top left there,

01:29:58.390 --> 01:30:03.440
an example of a manuscript
version, which on that kind

01:30:03.440 --> 01:30:04.740
of upper left there

01:30:04.740 --> 01:30:07.550
in the center what you
see is a whole bunch

01:30:07.550 --> 01:30:09.550
of those manuscript
cards stacked together

01:30:09.550 --> 01:30:12.040
with their own really
beautiful box next to it.

01:30:12.040 --> 01:30:16.140
So, even the manuscript rough
draft copy gets a beautiful

01:30:16.140 --> 01:30:17.440
leather box.

01:30:17.440 --> 01:30:20.770
Anyway, and then you also
see the printed cards there.

01:30:20.770 --> 01:30:22.840
So you can see how they
were printed at Frogmore,

01:30:22.840 --> 01:30:24.410
on the press at Frogmore.

01:30:24.410 --> 01:30:27.230
Printed cards and boxes
about Spain, Germany, France,

01:30:27.230 --> 01:30:30.660
Portugal, and Rome, or United
States of America you'd say.

01:30:30.660 --> 01:30:32.810
So how might these have
reflected the work of some

01:30:32.810 --> 01:30:36.590
of the important historian
of the day like Macaulay?

01:30:36.590 --> 01:30:39.760
The queen herself was also
writing historical accounts

01:30:39.760 --> 01:30:41.730
that reflected her
veracious reading.

01:30:41.730 --> 01:30:44.170
She may have been like her
husband and many others

01:30:44.170 --> 01:30:46.520
of their era copying
work she read

01:30:46.520 --> 01:30:49.050
or combining her own thoughts
and words with those of others.

01:30:49.050 --> 01:30:51.320
And I've been reading in
her historical accounts.

01:30:51.320 --> 01:30:54.970
She began to keep careful track
for example of the history

01:30:54.970 --> 01:30:57.770
and lineage of Sophia,
Electress of Hanover.

01:30:57.770 --> 01:31:00.040
There are two copies in
the queen's handwriting

01:31:00.040 --> 01:31:02.040
of the lineage of Sophia.

01:31:02.040 --> 01:31:04.900
Why would she be
writing multiple times

01:31:04.900 --> 01:31:08.210
about Sophia the
Electress of Hanover?

01:31:08.210 --> 01:31:10.310
Well, those of you
who know your 17th

01:31:10.310 --> 01:31:13.280
and 18th century English
history will know exactly why.

01:31:13.280 --> 01:31:15.940
Because this was-- She was
the granddaughter of James I

01:31:15.940 --> 01:31:19.300
and this was the lineage that
would shift the British monarchy

01:31:19.300 --> 01:31:22.010
from the Stewarts to the
Hanovers with George I

01:31:22.010 --> 01:31:23.680
and would bring Charlotte
to England

01:31:23.680 --> 01:31:26.020
as the consort of George III.

01:31:26.020 --> 01:31:28.450
She wrote out this
history of Sophia,

01:31:28.450 --> 01:31:31.050
Electress of Hanover
multiple times.

01:31:31.050 --> 01:31:33.530
How meaningful that was
and yet how contested

01:31:33.530 --> 01:31:35.440
in the many histories
of the 17th century

01:31:35.440 --> 01:31:37.160
and earlier that she had read.

01:31:37.160 --> 01:31:39.540
How consequential in
the 18th centuries

01:31:39.540 --> 01:31:41.160
through to what she was living.

01:31:41.160 --> 01:31:43.610
These are just a few of
the extraordinary stories

01:31:43.610 --> 01:31:47.530
and connections that we can
pull out of the Georgian Papers.

01:31:47.530 --> 01:31:49.990
And I want to suggest
that if you want

01:31:49.990 --> 01:31:52.740
to explore the Georgian
Papers yourself,

