women.

01:46:55.240 --> 01:46:57.920
But the women's history
opportunities in these archives

01:46:57.920 --> 01:47:00.680
and the opportunities to link
materials in those archives

01:47:00.680 --> 01:47:02.080
with other archives here

01:47:02.080 --> 01:47:04.420
in the United States
is really incredible.

01:47:04.420 --> 01:47:07.520
There are all kinds of things
we can learn about, you know,

01:47:07.520 --> 01:47:10.190
women's consumption
patterns, about food,

01:47:10.190 --> 01:47:12.060
about ideas about the body.

01:47:12.060 --> 01:47:13.360
And there are just-- Anyway,

01:47:13.360 --> 01:47:14.870
they are just endless
opportunities

01:47:14.870 --> 01:47:16.580
and those will translate
to teaching.

01:47:16.580 --> 01:47:17.880
&gt;&gt; Arthur Burns: I
think one thing you have

01:47:17.880 --> 01:47:19.180
to example is Princess Amelia

01:47:19.180 --> 01:47:20.920
and her experience
of consumption.

01:47:20.920 --> 01:47:22.620
Now there's another
extraordinary medical

01:47:22.620 --> 01:47:23.920
case history.

01:47:23.920 --> 01:47:28.730
Lived from the inside by royal
princess has also infatuated one

01:47:28.730 --> 01:47:32.730
of your queries, so does the
extraordinary romantic story

01:47:32.730 --> 01:47:36.080
of that new kind of
romantic love being embodied

01:47:36.080 --> 01:47:38.940
in that situation in
[inaudible], days we're looking

01:47:38.940 --> 01:47:42.310
at that, an extraordinary
material that she's found there.

01:47:42.310 --> 01:47:45.390
And that was a great story
about how digital works as well,

01:47:45.390 --> 01:47:48.250
because we broadcast the
documentary on the BBC

01:47:48.250 --> 01:47:50.180
and there's a brief
section where Flora Fraser,

01:47:50.180 --> 01:47:52.220
one of our fellows who is one

01:47:52.220 --> 01:47:56.250
of our Mount Vernon
professors, talks about this.

01:47:56.250 --> 01:47:58.130
And the next day, I got a
friendly call from somewhere

01:47:58.130 --> 01:47:59.720
in the north saying, "I
think I've got the other half

01:47:59.720 --> 01:48:01.020
of the correspondence."

01:48:01.020 --> 01:48:03.610
And it was ascendant
to one of the queries

01:48:03.610 --> 01:48:04.960
that she's involved with.

01:48:04.960 --> 01:48:06.260
So we've been up there.

01:48:06.260 --> 01:48:08.350
We haven't yet found what we
can do that an idea would be

01:48:08.350 --> 01:48:11.170
to digitize those documents
and bring those in as well.

01:48:11.170 --> 01:48:12.470
And that's what you
can do with digital.

01:48:12.470 --> 01:48:15.330
You can create virtual
archives without having to mess

01:48:15.330 --> 01:48:17.130
about with physical
archives themselves.

01:48:17.130 --> 01:48:19.130
And it's fantastic
we can do that.

01:48:19.130 --> 01:48:21.420
&gt;&gt; Karin Wulf: Those medical--
The medical history as a kind

01:48:21.420 --> 01:48:23.680
of theme throughout is really
compelling with George III

01:48:23.680 --> 01:48:26.390
of course and Amelia
and Fanny Burney has one

01:48:26.390 --> 01:48:29.390
of the most famous women's
medical histories of the period

01:48:29.390 --> 01:48:32.860
where she, you know,
narrated her own mastectomy.

01:48:32.860 --> 01:48:34.700
She writes about
having done it under--

01:48:34.700 --> 01:48:36.000
you know, with no anesthesia.

01:48:36.000 --> 01:48:44.270
It's a really extraordinary
document in women's history.

01:48:44.270 --> 01:48:46.570
&gt;&gt; Yes?

01:48:51.780 --> 01:48:55.920
&gt;&gt; I'd read recently in
recent years about the--

01:48:55.920 --> 01:48:59.330
that one of the key
reasons for the loss in 1780

01:48:59.330 --> 01:49:03.400
in Cornwallis was that
half of the British troops

01:49:03.400 --> 01:49:05.230
in America had been diverted

01:49:05.230 --> 01:49:09.010
to the West Indies
to protect the sugar.

01:49:09.010 --> 01:49:11.990
And given what you've
referred to as--

01:49:11.990 --> 01:49:14.890
and we've seen other places
about the king's involvement

01:49:14.890 --> 01:49:20.200
of this, it's hard to quite
imagine him either suggesting

01:49:20.200 --> 01:49:22.750
or allowing that diversion.

01:49:22.750 --> 01:49:26.070
Is there anything that's
come to light about that?

01:49:26.070 --> 01:49:29.370
&gt;&gt; Andrew O'Shaughnessy: He
actually supported that policy

01:49:29.370 --> 01:49:32.940
and said, "We can't even
fight the American war

01:49:32.940 --> 01:49:35.140
without our sugar items."

01:49:35.140 --> 01:49:41.990
And so in 1778, when the British
had occupied Philadelphia,

01:49:41.990 --> 01:49:46.170
the new commander-in-chief Henry
Clinton was given orders to give

01:49:46.170 --> 01:49:49.320
up Philadelphia to
send 5000 troops

01:49:49.320 --> 01:49:52.310
down to the Caribbean
to take Saint Lucia.

01:49:52.310 --> 01:49:57.540
And then in the summer of 1779,
the British received warning

01:49:57.540 --> 01:49:59.040
that Jamaica was
about to be invaded.

01:49:59.040 --> 01:50:02.130
They put their entire army
in New York onboard ship

01:50:02.130 --> 01:50:05.650
with Cornwallis and they were
at sea for almost a week.

01:50:05.650 --> 01:50:09.360
So this really shows
you the priorities.

01:50:09.360 --> 01:50:12.160
They did lose a large number

01:50:12.160 --> 01:50:14.920
of their islands
during the revolution.

01:50:14.920 --> 01:50:17.520
But it seems to have been kind

01:50:17.520 --> 01:50:22.760
of one compromise they're
willing to make was

01:50:22.760 --> 01:50:26.010
to lose Jamaica, So they're
actually sending more troops

01:50:26.010 --> 01:50:27.560
to the West Indies in the second

01:50:27.560 --> 01:50:33.580
of the American Revolution
then to America.

01:50:33.580 --> 01:50:36.740
&gt;&gt; Dr. Colleen J.
Shogan: Over here?

01:50:36.740 --> 01:50:39.830
&gt;&gt; Thanks again to all of you
for wonderful presentations.

01:50:39.830 --> 01:50:43.320
I'm wondering if any
of you has any sense

01:50:43.320 --> 01:50:49.090
that this project might
stimulate contextualization

01:50:49.090 --> 01:50:51.850
with parallel archives

01:50:51.850 --> 01:50:55.580
for example among the royal
houses elsewhere in Europe

01:50:55.580 --> 01:50:59.830
or perhaps even more
pertinently,

01:50:59.830 --> 01:51:04.610
papers of British aristocratic
families and households and so

01:51:04.610 --> 01:51:08.590
on or perhaps such
already exist?

01:51:08.590 --> 01:51:10.220
&gt;&gt; Arthur Burns: So, we
know already there are one

01:51:10.220 --> 01:51:13.770
or two other projects that
are beginning to talk to us,

01:51:13.770 --> 01:51:15.690
some of the kind that you've
mentioned is we've got an

01:51:15.690 --> 01:51:16.990
addition of one

01:51:16.990 --> 01:51:19.500
of the courtier's papers that's
proceeding in Manchester.

01:51:19.500 --> 01:51:21.000
They're not talking
to us, we're hoping

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:23.850
to align transcription,
launch that.

01:51:23.850 --> 01:51:25.810
And there are various
tensions raised

01:51:25.810 --> 01:51:27.110
and [inaudible] we
hope we'll be able

01:51:27.110 --> 01:51:29.060
to build links possibly
even fellowships of the kind

01:51:29.060 --> 01:51:30.830
that we've had elsewhere
to bring people

01:51:30.830 --> 01:51:32.970
in to work with the papers.

01:51:32.970 --> 01:51:36.450
I think the competitive
monarchs things is a point very

01:51:36.450 --> 01:51:37.750
well taken.

01:51:37.750 --> 01:51:40.480
We're in touch with a scholar
in Leiden, Jeroen Duindam,

01:51:40.480 --> 01:51:42.200
who wrote a-- I think it's
a book called Dynasty.

01:51:42.200 --> 01:51:44.310
You may know it, which
is global history

01:51:44.310 --> 01:51:46.640
of monarchy in any
modern period.

01:51:46.640 --> 01:51:48.830
He's just got some
money to do a project

01:51:48.830 --> 01:51:50.470
on Northern European monarchies.

01:51:50.470 --> 01:51:53.250
And I'm talking to him about
what we might be able to do

01:51:53.250 --> 01:51:56.240
at some point for the workshops
to bring those together.

01:51:56.240 --> 01:51:58.490
And I think that that's
precisely the kind of thing

01:51:58.490 --> 01:51:59.900
that we want to see happen.

01:51:59.900 --> 01:52:02.660
And one of the nice thing about
the project, in some ways,

01:52:02.660 --> 01:52:04.090
it's a very unusual project.

01:52:04.090 --> 01:52:05.870
And we don't have a
research question.

01:52:05.870 --> 01:52:08.150
And usually now, when
you set out in Britain,

01:52:08.150 --> 01:52:09.800
like if you got a
particular question, you say,

01:52:09.800 --> 01:52:12.450
this is where I'm going to find
the answer and you hope you do

01:52:12.450 --> 01:52:14.180
and that's why you give
them the money to do it.

01:52:14.180 --> 01:52:16.840
Here, probably because we aren't
funded in a big research project

01:52:16.840 --> 01:52:19.550
without a single question,

01:52:19.550 --> 01:52:22.280
we can follow what the
archives suggest to us.

01:52:22.280 --> 01:52:24.980
And the key to that is making
sure enough people know

01:52:24.980 --> 01:52:26.720
about what we're doing
and that's what links

01:52:26.720 --> 01:52:28.510
with them the Library
of Congress and others.

01:52:28.510 --> 01:52:31.820
It's so important that we can
then make those connections

01:52:31.820 --> 01:52:33.600
for as wide an audience
as you possibly can.

01:52:33.600 --> 01:52:35.600
And it's the fun of it too.

01:52:35.600 --> 01:52:37.220
&gt;&gt; Jim Ambuske: I think there's
evidence that it's beginning

01:52:37.220 --> 01:52:38.520
to inspire the project.

01:52:38.520 --> 01:52:40.390
So we were just in
Scotland three weeks ago

01:52:40.390 --> 01:52:43.140
at our Scottish Records
Conference and met

01:52:43.140 --> 01:52:44.440
with the archivist at the Duke--

01:52:44.440 --> 01:52:46.790
of Duke of Argyll at
the Inveraray Castle.

01:52:46.790 --> 01:52:48.860
And they are beginning
to make public

01:52:48.860 --> 01:52:51.800
and more accessible not
necessarily to digital means

01:52:51.800 --> 01:52:54.630
but more accessible, the
papers of the Dukes of Argyll

01:52:54.630 --> 01:52:57.240
who are the most powerful
family in 18th century Scotland.

01:52:57.240 --> 01:53:00.030
And so you're getting
to see, you know,

01:53:00.030 --> 01:53:02.060
I think some momentum
built up to open

01:53:02.060 --> 01:53:06.160
up these once very closed
bases to new research.

01:53:06.160 --> 01:53:07.860
&gt;&gt; Karin Wulf: I'll just add
one quick thing there which is

01:53:07.860 --> 01:53:10.170
that through these back
and forth fellowships

01:53:10.170 --> 01:53:13.580
of having fellows in one archive
and then in the other at Windsor

01:53:13.580 --> 01:53:15.660
and at the Library of Congress
and hopefully in other back

01:53:15.660 --> 01:53:19.330
and forth spaces, you commit the
fellows really to helping talk

01:53:19.330 --> 01:53:21.790
to all of us about what's
mutually in those things.

01:53:21.790 --> 01:53:24.180
We can read an academic
monograph and see, oh,

01:53:24.180 --> 01:53:26.940
you've used archival materials
in this place and this place.

01:53:26.940 --> 01:53:29.400
They must connect
in some logical way.

01:53:29.400 --> 01:53:33.560
But because the fellows are, you
know, fellows of the project,

01:53:33.560 --> 01:53:35.810
they actually provide
support back to the project

01:53:35.810 --> 01:53:38.200
on exactly these
questions of linkages.

01:53:38.200 --> 01:53:39.500
&gt;&gt; Arthur Burns: One of
the interesting things

01:53:39.500 --> 01:53:41.510
about our period, I
think, is attentive

01:53:41.510 --> 01:53:43.660
of what situation the
US is but in the UK,

01:53:43.660 --> 01:53:46.560
the 18th century is the most
digital of all centuries.

01:53:46.560 --> 01:53:49.390
More pioneering work is being
done in digital amenities.

01:53:49.390 --> 01:53:52.660
We have the Old Bailey online
where every criminal case

01:53:52.660 --> 01:53:54.530
at that Old Bailey
is readable online.

01:53:54.530 --> 01:53:57.370
We have records of all
the London workhouses.

01:53:57.370 --> 01:54:00.580
We have records of every
murder that happened

01:54:00.580 --> 01:54:02.890
in London plotted onto maps.

01:54:02.890 --> 01:54:05.650
And so all these things
might include your database

01:54:05.650 --> 01:54:08.310
for every [inaudible]
you bring those together

01:54:08.310 --> 01:54:09.870
and we're beginning
to create a kind

01:54:09.870 --> 01:54:12.960
of unique digital environment
as well, which we can just--

01:54:12.960 --> 01:54:15.510
there's a thing called connected
histories now where you can type

01:54:15.510 --> 01:54:18.430
in John-- well, don't
type in John Smith.

01:54:18.430 --> 01:54:21.950
But if you found a slightly
more unusual name, type it in,

01:54:21.950 --> 01:54:25.250
and it will tell you which of
those databases have references

01:54:25.250 --> 01:54:26.550
to that name.

01:54:26.550 --> 01:54:28.380
And the possibility of
linking them all up in

01:54:28.380 --> 01:54:29.860
that way is a very exciting

01:54:29.860 --> 01:54:31.490
and slightly daunting
prospect as well.

